<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-Up: FTAA Needs New Push </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, Chile, April 17 (Xinhua) -- After four years of the
kick-off, The Second Summit of the Americas scheduled to open here
tomorrow will give a new push for the slow process of the Free
Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA).
</P>
<P>
Initiated by U.S. President Bill Clinton, 34 leaders of the
West Hemisphere gathered in Miami in December 1994 to conceive a
blueprint for the establishment of a free trade zone by 2005. The
FTAA could become the World's largest tariff-free area with a
combined population of 750 million and gross domestic product
exceeding 9 trillion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally regarded as the "backyard" of the United States,
the region now accounts for some 38.6 percent of all U.S. exports,
with Latin American shipments expected to surpass those to Western
Europe and Japan combined by the year of 2010. The Clinton
administration attaches great importance to the FTAA
establishment.
</P>
<P>
At the 1994 summit, the 34 leaders agreed to a plan of action
that included 23 initiatives covered in four baskets: Preserving
and Strengthening of Democracy; Promoting Prosperity Through
Economic Integration and Free Trade; Eradicating Poverty and
Discrimation; and Guaranteeing Sustainable Development and
Conserving Our Natural Environment for Future Generations.
</P>
<P>
Since the Miami Summit, 12 working groups have been organized
to study and work out common positions on major issues linked to
trade and investment, assisted by a tripartite commission from the
Inter-American Development Bank (IDB), the UN Economic Commission
for latin America and the Caribbean and the Organization of
American States (OAS).
</P>
<P>
In the last less than four years, relevant ministerial meetings
of foreign affairs, trade, treasury, energy, defense, justice,
transportation and education have been convened. Under the Trade
Committee, there are working groups which undertook discussions on
some major topics such as market access, agriculture and financial
services.
</P>
<P>
The Santiago Summit will be focused on Education issues which
form a basket itself-- Education: Investing in People' Defining
Our Shared Future. Other topics of the meeting include Making
Democracy Relevant, Enjoying the Fruits of Freedom, Building Our
Wealth Through Economic Integration and Trade, Rejecting Poverty
Amid Growing Prosperity, which form other three baskets.
</P>
<P>
The Second Summit of the Americas is to evaluate progress
achieved since Miami and synthesize the concrete actions that
governments must take to further open their markets to private
investment and to deepen democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
The 34-nation trade ministers held another meeting in San Jose,
Costa Rica a month ago. The participants concluded a frame
agreement over principles and goals of the proposed trade
negotiations. Once the Santiago Summit gives green light to the
ministerial agreement, the official negotiations would kick off as
early as May. The Santiago Summit could an important milestone for
the development of the FTAA.
</P>
<P>
For realization of the FTAA, the Americas prevail some
favorable conditions: first, in recent years, there have formed
stable political, economic and social environment throughout the
hemisphere which is attributable largely to political and economic
reforms.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, in the wake of the Uruguay Round of trade talks, the
Latin American and Caribbean nations gradually gave up the
close-door policies and government intervention, turning to
market-oriented economic policies. At present all 34 Americas
except Bahamas are members of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
And thirdly, there have been active agenda of free trade area
negotiations in the hemisphere. Apart from the three-nation North
American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) and the four-nation MERCOSUR
in Southern America, we have witnessed in the past year the
conclusion of the Chile-Canada Free Trade Area (FTA), the
MERCOSUR-Chile FTA, and the MERCOSUR-Bolivia FTA, as well as the
initiation of negotiation between MERCOSUR and the Andean Pact,
between Panama and Chile, between Mexico and Northern Triangle of
Central America and between Central America and the islands of the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
However, in order to fulfil the 34 nation leaders' mandate for
"concrete progress by the end of the century", there still exist a
number of obstacles and difficulties. The FTAA was initiated by
the United States. But, since the Clinton administration failed to
admit Chile into the NAFTA as it pledged and lost its battle for
foreign trade "fast track" authorization in 1997, the U.S.
government is much less convincing for advocating for free trade
in the hemisphere and official negotiations could be delayed until
2000 or after.
</P>
<P>
Besides, there have been disagreement over the FTAA negotiation
pace between the U.S. and Brazil. The former advocates for
accelerating agenda and the later holds for "gradualism" for
consolidation of the MERCOSUR first and then move to FTAA
negotiations. The United States targets the free trade area as a
large market of 750 million population for its exports. But the
Latin American and Caribbean countries are more concerned for
their social and economic development. The FTAA negotiations would
involve some interest-conflicted groups such as organizations of
labor, environmentalists and consumers as well as some other
non-governmental groups. Each inch of progress in the future
negotiations would be fought seriously and furiously.
</P>
<P>
Although there has been not a bad start, there is still a long
way to go to reach the FTAA and the process obviously needs new
push. 
</P>
</TEXT>
