<HEADLINE> WHO Confident of Control River Blindness by 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) has announced that a program to control the disease, river
blindness, in West Africa will end in 2002 due to its success over
the last 25 years.
</P>
<P>
The Onchocerciasis Control Program, which cost half a billion
U.S. dollars, will protect over 40 million people from the disease
and about 600,000 from blindness, WHO said.
</P>
<P>
The disease, called onchocerciasis or river blindness, is
transmitted by the bite of the black flies which release into the
human bodies tiny worms (microfilaria). These tiny worms cause
unbearable itching, skin disfigurement and blindness.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the program sponsored by the World Bank, the United
Nations Development Program, the U.N. Food and Agriculture
Organization and WHO, gone are the days when up to 50 percent of
the adult population over 30 percent in rural areas of West Africa
suffered from the disease.
</P>
<P>
Further surveillance to detect reinfection and rapid protection
of the concerned population by treatment with ivermectin is
required and must be maintained for the foreseeable future, WHO
added.
</P>
<P>
WHO also wants to integrate the surveillance into a
multi-disease surveillance system primarily oriented towards
epidemic-prone diseases such as cholera, meningitis, yellow fever
and malaria after the Onchocerciasis Control Program terminates in
2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
