<HEADLINE> Kiriyenko Expresses Concerns on Economic Drop in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian Acting Prime Minister
Sergei Kiriyenko has warned of a possible drop of the country's
economic growth rate due to unstable political situation.
</P>
<P>
After the State Duma's (the lower house of parliament) second
refusal to approve his nomination as prime minister on Friday,
Kiriyenko said that the unstable political situation would affect
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The sooner the government crisis was over, the better it would
be for the Russian economy, Kiriyenko said.
</P>
<P>
There were different estimations of economic growth rates in
the first quarter of this year, he said, but the situation was
generally worse than it was in the fourth quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
The acting premier also expressed his concern on the
possibility to dissolve the State Duma.
</P>
<P>
The president has the constitutional right to dissolve the Duma
if it rejects his candidates for the premiership three times, he
said.
</P>
<P>
But the refused nominee said he was not interested in
"political games" and would not be involved in any bargaining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
