<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Urged to Continue Trade Reforms to Maintain Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Trade Organization (WTO)
has urged India to continue liberalizing its trade and investment
structures to ensure strong and stable economic growth.
</P>
<P>
After a two-day meeting, the WTO released a report on India's
trade policies and practices.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that India's economic growth slowed in
1997 after its reforms and trade liberalization policies led to a
dramatic increase in the mid-1990's.
</P>
<P>
Due to large flows of foreign investment and increased
international trade, India had achieved annual average growth
rates of 7 percent from 1993 to 1996, the report said.
</P>
<P>
India had recognized the need to continue economic reform, with
an increased emphasis on improving its industrial infrastructure,
which had proved to be a constraint on expanding economic activity
and stimulating exports.
</P>
<P>
Other measures under consideration were reductions in tariffs
and non-tariff measures, reforming the subsidies structure --
estimated to account for 14 percent of the GDP -- and
restructuring public sector enterprises.
</P>
<P>
India's tariffs had been reduced from an average of 71 percent
in 1993 to 35 percent now. However, the tariff structure remained
complex and escalation remained high in several industries,
notably paper and paper products, printing and publishing, wood
and wood products, and food, beverages and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
In general, the report said, bound tariffs remained
substantially higher than applied rates, especially on
agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
Import licensing remained India's main non-tariff barrier, the
report noted, although reforms to the system of restrictive import
licensing had moved ahead steadily.
</P>
<P>
The number of goods subject to import licensing had been
gradually reduced, with an emphasis on industrial and capital
goods, rather than consumer products.
</P>
<P>
The WTO report was not satisfied with the fact that India had
refrained from reforms on export subsidies and incentives and had
continued to maintain a large number of incentive programs for
exports.
</P>
<P>
It said that the overall scope of income tax exemptions,
subsidized credit, export insurances and guarantees has been
enhanced, resulting in more explicit export-oriented policies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
