<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIBC, TD Banks Make Canadian Biggest Corporate marriage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Imperial of Bank of
Commerce (CIBC) and Toronto-Dominion Bank (TD) announced their
merger Friday, which would be worth 45.8 billion Canadian dollars
(31.9 billion U. S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The deal comes close on the heels of the January announcement
of the biggest corporate marriage between the nation's biggest and
third biggest banks, the Royal and the Bank of Montreal.
</P>
<P>
Both deals are now waiting for blessing from the federal
government, which is apparently not happy with the mergermania in
the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
The merged bank, which would be called CIBC, will have a
combined assets of 460 billion Canadian dollars (322 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Once merged, it will become the second largest bank in Canada
and the 10th largest in North America in terms of market
capitalization, which was 45.8 billion Canadian dollars (40.9
billion U.S. dollars) at the close of trading on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The combined company will have more than 10 million customers
in Canada and around the globe, with more than 74,000 full-time
equivalent employees," CIBC and TD said in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
"This agreement will create a strong, competitive bank that is
Canadian-based," said Al Flood, CIBC chairman and chief executive
officer.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that this deal will make us better able to compete,
not only with domestic competitors but also with powerful
competitors from all over the world," added Charles Baillie,
Flood's TD counterpart.
</P>
<P>
But Canadian Finance Minister Paul Martin was not so sure about
all the benefits mergers will bring along.
</P>
<P>
"The No. 1 concern of the government remains what is good for
Canadians and the Canadian economy," Martin said Friday shortly
after the announcement.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the government will not consider such deals
until a full review of the industry is complete, perhaps by the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, bank merger frenzy has been sweeping the North
American continent. Friday's proposed merger was the third
multi-billion dollars bank merger announced this week alone.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, NationsBank Corp. and BankAmerica Corp. revealed a
plan to create the biggest bank in the United States, with assets
of 570 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
