<HEADLINE> UN Reports Iraq Has Made No New Progress in Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A new report presented by
the Executive Chairman of the United Nations Special Commission
(UNSCOM) Richard Butler says Friday that Iraq has made no new
progress in disarmament.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM, in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, is requested to present a report on the progress in
Iraq's disarmament in every six months.
</P>
<P>
The report says Iraq has so far failed to provide UNSCOM with
any new information on its weapons, and virtually no progress in
verifying disarmament has been made.
</P>
<P>
This report came after technical surveys that left questions
about Iraqi compliance in biological, chemical, nuclear and
missile programs.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council of the United Nations is expected to
consider this report early next week. It will also use the report
as a basis for deciding by the end of this month whether to ease
the tough economic sanctions imposed on Iraq after its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
