<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy Secures Ceasefire from Afghan Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Ambassador to the United
Nations Bill Richardson announced on Friday in Kabul that he had
secured a ceasefire from the Afghan Taliban militia and won their
agreement to hold talks with the opposition forces by April 27.
</P>
<P>
Richardson, who is visiting the region as a special envoy of
U.S. President Bill Clinton, said it was a major breakthrough in
the past 18 years, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Richardson, who arrived in Kabul earlier Friday, held a
two-hour meeting with Mullah Mohammad Rabbani, the second most
senior leader of the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
"It appears we have a breakthrough that if the northern
alliance agrees we will have talks between the Taliban and the
northern alliance in Islamabad before April 27," Richardson told
reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Until then we have the Taliban's commitment that there will be
no fresh Taliban offensive," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that it depends on deeds and not just words. But the
most important thing is "we have a process started that could lead
to talks under the U.N. auspices," he said.
</P>
<P>
Richardson also said the Taliban had agreed to release a
"significant number" of opposition prisoners in the next two days
in a goodwill gesture to back the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Richardson is scheduled to meet leaders of the anti-Taliban
alliance -- ethnic Uzbek warlord Abdul Rashid Dostum, ousted
president Burhannudin Rabbani and a Shiite faction leader Karim
Khalili in the opposition-held northern town of Sheberghan later
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said his aim in northern Afghanistan would be to
secure an agreement of the anti-Taliban alliance leadership to the
same deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
