<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Intensify Campaign on Partylist System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Commission on
Elections (Comelec) said Friday that it will intensify its massive
information dissemination on the party-list system to be used for
the first time in the May 11 general elections.
</P>
<P>
Comelec Director Augusto Toledo told reporters that the
commission started this week its information campaign nationwide
to explain to the people the importance of the party-list system.
</P>
<P>
The party-list system is a mechanism of proportional
representation in the election of members to the House of
Representatives from marginalized or under-represented parties.
</P>
<P>
It enables small political parties and marginalized and
under-represented sectors to obtain possible representation in the
lower chamber which, traditionally, is dominated by parties with
big political machinery.
</P>
<P>
Instead of individual candidates, only registered organized
groups such as sectoral groups from labor, peasants, urban poor,
indigenous cultural communities, elderly, handicapped, women,
youth, overseas workers, fisher folk, veterans and professionals
can participate in the party-list election.
</P>
<P>
A party should obtain at least 2 percent of the total votes
cast for the party-list system nationwide in order to be allocated
with one seat at the lower house; 4 percent for two seats; and 6
percent for three seats.
</P>
<P>
Toledo said that as of March 17, there were a total of 122
registered organized groups accredited by the Comelec to
participate in the coming May 11 elections.
</P>
<P>
He said all polling booths shall have a list of all candidates
running for elective positions, including those in the party-list.
</P>
<P>
Toledo said 20 percent of the total membership in the House of
Representatives are reserved for party-list representatives. For
this year, there will be 51 seats for sectoral representatives.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Toledo encouraged the different party-list
participants to help the Comelec disseminate information to the
more than 34 million registered voters all over the country
regarding the importance of the party-list system.
</P>
<P>
The country's first party-list election will be held
simultaneously with the national and local elections during which
voters will also elect the president, the vice president, 12 of
the 20 senators, 204 members of the lower house by constituency,
and thousands of local officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
