<HEADLINE> Security Beefed Up in Food Warehouses in Famine-hit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Police authorities have
strengthened security measures in six warehouses of the National
Food Authority (NFA) in a famine-hit southern Philippine province
to thwart any attempt to ransack the facilities, a food official
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
NFA provincial manager Remegio Samsom said police authorities
have doubled the number of cops deployed in the warehouses in
South Cotabato province and strengthened detective surveillance
around the facilities.
</P>
<P>
Samson explained that the additional security is in response to
reports that several groups are out to ransack NFA warehouses in
nearby Sultan Kudarat province.
</P>
<P>
"We did not receive any similar threat, but, it is better for
us to be prepared," Samson said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that with the present food shortage problem brought
about by the El Nino-induced long drought in the province, it is
possible that certain groups will ransack grain warehouses.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Red Cross on Thursday called for donations from
the private sector in order to ease the food shortage problem in
Mindanao, the southern Philippines, where about 2.2 million people
have been affected.
</P>
<P>
A massive food shortage has hit Mindanao since last month as
months of dry spells caused by El Nino rendered almost thousands
of hectares of farmland in the region parched up.
</P>
<P>
El Nino, a weather phenomenon caused by recurrent ocean warming
and atmospheric disturbance in the Southern Pacific, began to hit
the Philippines in the last quarter of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
