<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Decides Immediate Withdrawal of UN Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- UN secretary-General Kofi
Annan has decided to withdraw immediately the investigation team
he sent to the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) to look into
allegations of serious violations of human rights and
international humanitarian law in certain parts of the country, UN
Spokesman Fred Eckhard announced on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the investigation team was intended to
bridge the impasse which had arisen as a result of the refusal of
the Government of DRC to allow a Joint Investigative Mission of
the Commission on Human Rights to investigate the allegation.
</P>
<P>
However, since its arrival in DRC in August 1997, the
investigation team constantly met a series of obstacles by the DRC
authorities.
</P>
<P>
In the most recent incident in this pattern of obstruction, the
DRC authorities on April 7 and 8 expelled a member of
investigation team form the investigation site and subsequently
detained him at Kinshasa airport.
</P>
<P>
Confidential UN documents in the possession of the staff member
were seized, searched and assumed to have been photocopied by the
DRC authorities in complete disregards of the obligations of
Member States under the Convention on the Privileges and
Immunities of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
In the light of the total absence of cooperation of the
Government of DRC in allowing the investigation team to carry out
its work, and following a careful assessment made by a mission
sent by the Secretary-General for this purpose, Annan decided to
withdrew the team with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
The Commission on Human rights, under its mandate, remains
seized of the question of allegations regarding serious violations
of human rights and international humanitarian law in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
