<HEADLINE> Somalia: Hostage Release Efforts Meet With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Efforts to secure the hostages
of the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) kidnaped
by some Somali gunmen in Mogadishu on Wednesday have met with
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Somali Faction leader Ali Mahdi Mohamed, since his arrival on
Thursday night, has not spared a minute in securing the safe
release of the 10 aid workers of the ICRC abducted at the Issaley
airstrip.
</P>
<P>
Faction leader Osman Ali Atto, together with other officials
from his faction and some local politicians, were also in north
Mogadishu Friday working for the release of the ICRC aid workers.
</P>
<P>
The release efforts have also been joined by the the
prestigious lmam of Abgal, lmam Mohamud lmam Omar, Mogadishu's
former mayor Ali Ugas Abdulle and many other Abgal traditional
leaders.
</P>
<P>
It was said that the abductors have elected eight members from
their side to represent them in the talks they are having with
the Abgal traditional leaders.
</P>
<P>
Several attempts have already been made in securing their
release, but it seems that each time some new difficulties have
been encountered.
</P>
<P>
According to one of Osman Atto's officials and the local
Somali Red Crescent society workers, all of the kidnaped are
doing fine and fed well.
</P>
<P>
Though the Red Crescent workers believe that the current
efforts may lead to the release of the hostages by the end of
Friday, the story doesn't seem to come to an end on Friday
despite all efforts.
</P>
<P>
Mogadishu's Joint Health Authority (JHA) Friday condemned the
continuous abduction of the ICRC staff members in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
JHA Coordinator Osman Mohamud Dufle has characterized the
abduction as " inhumane " and contrary to what he called the
noble task of the ICRC in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
JHA has called for the immediate and unconditional release of
the ICRC aid workers, whom have come to Somalia for further
improving the humanitarian operations of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
