<HEADLINE> Chile, Mexico Sign Two Agreements to Expand Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, Chile, April 17 (Xinhua) -- President Eduardo Frei
Ruiz-Tagle of Chile and President Eduardo Zedillo Ponce de Leon
Friday signed two agreements in a bid to expand economic ties
between the two Latin American nations.
</P>
<P>
The two accords include the Enlargement of the Economic
Complementation Agreement (EECA) and a Pact to Avoid the Double
Taxation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The EECA is signed to replace the original one signed in 1991.
The new accord has contained some sectors such as services and
telecommunications which were excluded in the previous agreement.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Chilean and Mexican trade relations have
developed rapidly. The two-way trade amount increased from only
158.4 million U.S. dollars in 1990 to some 1452 million dollars
last year as a result of enhanced cooperation between the two
nations.
</P>
<P>
As regarding to the Agreement to Avoid Double Taxation, it
represents a great advance for the cooperation between
entrepreneurs of both nations and region-wide as well, because cost
reduction due to tax charges will not only benefit the two
countries, but also their neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
