<HEADLINE> Strong Pound Might Cause UK Recession, BCC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 17 (Xinhua) - British industry has urged Bank of
England to call a halt to interest rises as evidence showed that
impact caused by the strong pound has spread from manufacturing
into the services sector.
</P>
<P>
Export sales and orders for UK firms have slumped to a
seven-year low, according the latest quarterly economic survey
from the British Chambers of Commerce(BCC).
</P>
<P>
Currency traders ignored the weak data to send the pound
surging higher again on the foreign exchanges as concern mounted
over deepening divisions in the Bank of England's monetary policy
committee.
</P>
<P>
Sterling climbed three pennies to DM3.0592 against the mark
and its trade weighted index rose a full point to 108.1 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The sterling index, which measures the pound's average
international value, climbed from 107.1 to 108.1, close to the
10-year high touched earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Confirming other evidence of the weak state of manufacturing in
the first few months of this year, the survey revealed slower
employment growth and lower investment intentions.
</P>
<P>
Analysts in the City believe that collapsing export growth will
produce weak GDP growth in both the first and second quarters.
</P>
<P>
Ian Peters, deputy director-general of the BCC, said: "There is
no justification for further interest rate rises. The Bank of
England must now display a united front and make it clear that
interest rates have peaked."
</P>
<P>
"Failure to do so, or a decision to raise interest rates
further, may be all that is needed to tip the manufacturing sector
into recession," he warned.
</P>
<P>
However, for the second month in a row, according to the
minutes of the Monetary Policy Committee, Eddie George, the
Governor of the Bank, had to use his casting vote to keep interest
rates unchanged in February and March.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates in Britain have remained flat at 7.25 percent since
November, having risen five times since the general election last
May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
