<HEADLINE> Angola Denies Its Troops Presence in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Angola's Ministry of Defense
Friday categorically denied that it has sent troops to Mozambique
to "sabotage the first local elections after peace achieves
there."
</P>
<P>
Defense Ministry spokesman Bravo Da Rosa made the announcement
to the media here, saying that there is not a single soldier in
the northern city of Beira and elsewhere in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Rosa said that the reports on this issue from some
foreign news agencies are "groundless."
</P>
<P>
These days some foreign newspapers have been carrying stories
claiming that Angolan troops had been deployed to Mozambique to
obstruct and sabotage the local elections scheduled to be held in
June, and Rosa said the Angolan Defense Ministry was shocked to
learn of such false reports.
</P>
<P>
He noted that no Angolan armed forces has ever been deployed
to the Mozambican territory.
</P>
<P>
In term of bilateral cooperation in military technologies,
Rosa admitted that Angola and Mozambique has signed a protocol of
intention in the field of officers training.
</P>
<P>
"There are no Mozambican troops in Angola and there are no
Angolan troops in Mozambique, either," he said, since the
protocol has not been implemented yet. 
</P>
