<HEADLINE> Mkapa Presses for Miners' Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 17 (Xinhua) -- President Benjamin Mkapa
Friday said his government will review safety measures in mines
to avert further unnecessary disasters, a report reaching here
from the northern region of Arusha said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing villagers at Mererani in Arusha, where more than 90
people are feared to have been buried alive last week, Mkapa said
his government is concerned with the safety of miners, and will
do whatever possible to ensure that there is enough protection
for them.
</P>
<P>
The miners, mostly aged between 12 and 25, were buried by a
landslide following heavy rains last Thursday. So far, eight
bodies have been identified.
</P>
<P>
The rescue operation has gained momentum following the arrival
of six high-voltage submersible pumps from Geita, Moshi and Tanga
areas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Australia has provided equipment worth 5,000 U.S.
Dollars for the rescue operation, including a submersible pump,
masks, gloves, ropes, high power torches and batteries.
</P>
<P>
The president, who came back Thursday evening from a state
visit to China, also assured small-scale miners in the area that
the government will offer equipment to guarantee their safety
inside the mining pits.
</P>
<P>
"We have been deeply touched with the loss of lives in
Mererani, and we should learn lessons from it to avert any such
disasters in the future," he said to some 4,000 villagers.
</P>
<P>
According to Mkapa, efforts are also underway to exchange
experiences with South Africa and Zimbabwe, which have been in
the mining business for a long time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
