<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Prime Minister Holds Talks with Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Visiting British Prime Minister
Tony Blair held talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
here Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
Blair arrived here Friday afternoon on a two-day visit to Egypt
as part of his multi-leg maiden tour of the Middle East aimed at
giving a shot to the stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Blair, accompanied by a team of diplomats specialized in Middle
East affairs and a number of journalists, was greeted at the
airport by Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri.
</P>
<P>
The talks between Mubarak and Blair will focus on the European
role in helping break a year-long stalemate in the Mideast peace
process. Britain is currently holding the rotating presidency of
the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been bogged down for
13-month over the Israeli construction of a Jewish settlement in
Arab East Jerusalem and over the scope and time scale of an
overdue Israeli pullback from the West Bank. Negotiations on the
Syrian and Lebanese tracks have been on ice since February 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ways of fostering Anglo-Egyptian economic relations
will figure high during Blair's talks with the Egyptian leader.
Britain is Egypt's second largest non-Arab investor after the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Blair, on his debut trip to the region since taking office last
year, will explore prospects for stronger ties with Egypt during
meetings with Ganzouri and Foreign Minister Amr Moussa Saturday.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, he is also scheduled to meet with members of the
British-Egyptian businessmen Association to examine the
possibility of increasing joint investments.
</P>
<P>
During his Cairo trip, Blair will meet with Grand Sheikh of
Al-Azhar Mohamed Sayed Tantawi, Egypt's top religious scholar,
before leaving for Saudi Arabia, the second leg in his Mideast
tour which will also take him to Jordan, Israel and the
Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
The tour comes at a time when Europe is urged to play a more
active role in the stalemated Mideast peace process, especially
since the U.S.-dominated mediation efforts have so far failed to
unlock the peace logjam. U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross will
begin a new round of shuttle diplomacy in the region in the coming
days.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, who toured the region
last month, was snubbed in Israel allegedly for breaching an
understanding on the arrangements of his visit to the Har Homa in
East Jerusalem. Israel's Jewish settlement construction work at
the site is behind the long freeze in Palestinian-Israeli talks.
</P>
<P>
Britain has made it clear that the status of Jerusalem, the
thorniest issue in the Palestinian-Israeli track, should be
decided at the final stage of their negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Israel has repeatedly rejected European involvement in the
peace process, favoring an absolute mediating role for the
United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
