<HEADLINE> Uganda to Open Consulate in Kenya's Second City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Uganda government will open
a consulate in port Mombasa, the second largest city in Kenya, to
deal with ware-housing and dispatch of Ugandan imports and
exports from the port, a Ugandan minister has said.
</P>
<P>
Abel Rwendeire, visiting Ugandan Minister of State for Trade
and Industry, said Thursday the consulate would also deal with
harmonization of documents for goods of imports or exports so
that they could reach their destinations on time, the Kenya News
Agency (KNA) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
On a familiarization tour of the port, the Ugandan minister
appealed to the Kenya Port Authority (KPA) management to set
aside a specific place where cargo meant for export to Uganda is
kept within six months in order to eradicate the diversion of
export cargo to Kenya's local market.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Kenya and Uganda had agreed that all
bottlenecks hampering the smooth and efficient dispatch and
offloading of cargo would soon be addressed to.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with the Ugandan minister, Samuel Maneno,
chairman of the KPA Board of Directors, said higher tariffs at
the ware houses would be regularized in an effort to attract more
Ugandan imports and exports.
</P>
<P>
More than 600 containers destined for Uganda, a land-locked
country, were currently stockpiled at the port due to
documentation irregularities and bad road conditions between
Mombasa and the capital Nairobi, Maneno noted.
</P>
<P>
The KPA chairman added that information about goods to be
auctioned would be streamlined so that Ugandans could be able to
buy them by reading their daily newspapers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
