<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Oldest Person Dies in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Marie Louise Meilleur, the world's
oldest person, has died in the Ontario town of Corbell, reports
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Meilleur died peacefully Thursday afternoon at 117,
according to her daughter Olive Therrien who is 78 years old
herself.
</P>
<P>
"She's been very well until last week," the daughter was quoted
as saying. "She got a blood clot in her leg and it moved from her
leg into her lung."
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Meilleur had three daughters and one son who are living.
The oldest is 89.
</P>
<P>
She assumed the mantle of the world's oldest person after the
death of Frenchwoman Jeanne Calment at age 122.
</P>
<P>
The Guinness Book of World Records accepted her because some of
the other contenders didn't have the documentation Guinness
requires.
</P>
<P>
Born August 29, 1880, she had a life story almost as long as
her country Canada. She had six children children, some of whom
attended her last birthday party.
</P>
<P>
She had 85 grandchildren, 80 great-grandchildren, 57
great-great grandchildren and four great-great-great
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
The secret to her long life was hard work, according to her
72-year-old daughter Rita Gutzman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Germany's SPD Poises for Power Change in Bonn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Eager to put an end to the
misfortune of 16 years in opposition, Germany's leftist Social
Democratic Party (SPD) Friday formally endorsed Gerhard Schroeder
as its chancellor candidate and adopted an election platform
pledging to bring about changes and especially new jobs in the
country.
</P>
<P>
With only five months to go before the September 27 general
elections, the SPD confirmed the nomination of Schroeder,
54-year-old premier of the western German Lower Saxony state, by
an overwhelming majority of 93 percent of the vote at a special
party congress in the eastern German city of Leipzig on Friday.
</P>
<P>
As a pro-business moderate, Schroeder was widely seen as the
strongest SPD candidate since 1982 because he has more chance of
winning vital centrist votes, which are also much needed by German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's center-right ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
Declaring "the Kohl era is over," Schroeder told the 515
delegates at the congress that he was ready to take over the
German leadership to face challenges in a new century.
</P>
<P>
He pledged to make it the top priority of a SPD-led government
to fight the country's record high unemployment, a major rebuff
for Kohl's government, and to take a pragmatic approach to resolve
the problems facing Germany.
</P>
<P>
The SPD congress on Friday also adopted an election platform
calling for policy change in Bonn in order to achieve new economic
dynamic, new jobs, as well as to promote a new social culture
based on consensus and justice.
</P>
<P>
To fight unemployment, the SPD pledged more state spendings on
job creation and called for more flexible and shorter working
hours and more part-time jobs.
</P>
<P>
It also pledged to double state spendings on education and
research within the next five years and envisaged a gradual tax
reform aiming at cutting lowest income tax rate from the current
25.9 percent to 15 percent, and the highest tax rate from 53
percent to 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
Helped by rising public discontent with high unemployment and a
general desire for changes, the SPD has been leading Kohl's
Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party in almost all opinion polls
over the past one year.
</P>
<P>
The latest survey published by the German ZDF television
network on Friday also showed that if elections were held now, the
SPD would win 43 percent of the vote compared with just 35 percent
for Kohl's party.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Friday congress of the SPD, some critics,
however, pointed out that the party had failed to deliver a clear
message to launch fundamental economic reforms which are necessary
for Germany to withstand competitive pressures stemming both from
globalization as well as the new common European currency.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's CDU party on Friday also criticized the SPD platform as
full of rhetoric and lack in concrete details.
</P>
<P>
Despite his vulnerability after so many years in power, Kohl
has been open about the necessity for change while Schroeder has
been vague so far, political analysts argue.
</P>
<P>
Sharp criticism came also from Germany's Greens party on Friday
with one of its leaders, Juergen Trittin, saying that the SPD had
no concept to resolve the country's social problems.
</P>
<P>
It has been expected that the SPD would have to rely on an
alliance with the Greens to come to power after the elections.
</P>
<P>
However, the feasibility of such a "Red-Green" coalition has
been thrown into doubt recently after the Greens unveiled a series
of radical positions, calling for tripling the country's gasoline
prices and abolition of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO).
</P>
<P>
Given the uncertainty over the Red-Green alliance, there are
growing speculations about a possible grand coalition between the
CDU and the SPD. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Foreign Trade Improved in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Canada's exports and imports
improved in February, rising 2.2 and 0.9 percent respectively,
Statistics Canada reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Canada exported a total of 26.36 billion dollars' (18.45
billion USD) worth of goods to other countries in February, after
a fall of about one billion dollars in January.
</P>
<P>
"The machinery and equipment sector led the way with a solid
performance," the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
After slipping 1.4 percent in January, machinery and equipment
exports jumped 6.6 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
The increase was largely due to higher exports of television
and communications equipment to the Scandinavian countries and
railway equipment to the United States and Asia, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Canada's imports recovered slightly in
February, totalling 24.53 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Moderate growth in machinery and equipment, energy products,
and automotive product imports was partly offset by the declines
in imports of industrial goods and agriculture and fishing
products.
</P>
<P>
Canada's trade balance was 1.83 billion dollars in February, up
more than 300 million dollars from January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
