<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Lebanon, Syria to Launch Diplomatic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon and its ally Syria have
drafted a joint five-point diplomatic action plan to counter
Israel's conditional offer to pull its forces out of south
Lebanon, Lebanon's independent Central News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The plan came after intensive talks in Damascus Thursday among
Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and Foreign Minister Fares
Boueiz and Syrian Vice President Abdul-Halim Khaddam, according to
the news agency.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two sides reached an understanding on a
mechanism for a political and diplomatic action to explain the
background of the latest Israeli maneuver that is aimed at
scuttling the peace process.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, Israel, for the first time in the past two
decades, approved the United Nations Resolution 425 and offered
to withdraw its troops from south Lebanon in exchange for
Lebanese security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
Israel is now occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer border enclave
in south Lebanon with the claimed aim of protecting its northern
settlements from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
It has been also occupying Syria's Golan Heights since the 1967
Middle East War.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria have always insisted that their negotiations
with Israel be held simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
The two countries firmly rejected Israel's offer on the grounds
that the U.N. resolution 425 calls for an unconditional Israeli
withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
However, the two countries are facing the international
pressure to consider the offer seriously due to Israel's
diplomatic endeavors to promote its proposal in the world,
especially in the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Under the Lebanese-Syrian action plan, Lebanon will explain to
the world community why it finds the Israeli offer unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
It will also reply to the letter sent by U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright last week and another letter by French
Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
In her letter, Albright asked Lebanon to study Israel's
proposal seriously.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said in his letter that France strongly favors anything
that could bring about a solution satisfactory to Lebanon, Syria
and Israel.
</P>
<P>
According to the action plan, Lebanon will also send letters to
the five permanent members of the U.N. security council, the
non-aligned nations, members of the Arab League and others to
explain Lebanon's rejection to the Israeli offer.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Lebanese government will summon the
ambassadors of the five permanent members of the security council
in Beirut to explain Lebanon's position on the issue.
</P>
<P>
As part of the plan, Lebanese prime minister and foreign
minister will visit the five permanent members of the security
council as well as a number of Arab countries including Saudi
Arabia, Egypt and Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Their global tour is set to begin next Tuesday when Hariri
travels to Cairo for a previously arranged meeting with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
His visit to Egypt will come on the heels of Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad who held talks with Mubarak on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But no dates have been disclosed for visits to the other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese media predicted that Syria will carry out diplomatic
activities after assessing the outcome of the Lebanese efforts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shuttle Columbia Blasts Off From Cape Canaveral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. space shuttle Columbia
after one-day delay was launched into space Friday from Kennedy
Space Center, Cape Canaveral, at 2:19 p.m. EDP.
</P>
<P>
On its 25th flight, shuttle Columbia carried a seven-member
crew and a menagerie of more than 2,000 creatures,including
pregnant mice, rats, snails, fish and crickets.
</P>
<P>
During a two-week long flight, NASA scientists will conduct
26 biological experiments called the Neurolab. It is their hope
that these experiments would provide the most in-depth study
ever of the brain and nervous system in space. The seven
astronauts and menagerie of animals will serve as the test subjects.
</P>
<P>
Through these experiments, scientists want to know how the nervous
system adjusts to weightlessness, so as to make NASA in a better
position to send astronauts to Mars and establish moon colonies.
NASA also is eager to understand and solve some of the nagging
health problems such as insomnia, vertigo, imbalance, reduced
blood pressure, weakened immunity and dizziness upon landing.
</P>
<P>
Space shuttle Columbia, originally scheduled for blastoff on
Thursday, was postponed till today because one of it's two
network signal processors failed to receive signal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
