<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Automatic Sea Rescue System Turns 40 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Automated Mutual-assistance
Vessel Rescue system (AMVER) launches an international celebration
of 40 years of saving lives at sea this year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Coast Guard and the International Maritime
Organization created the worldwide search and rescue program 46
years after Titanic, the luxury liner's tragic accident. Lack of
communication during the Titanic's sinking produced new ideas for
protecting travel at sea.
</P>
<P>
In 1958, computer technology enabled the idea to become reality.
</P>
<P>
The AMVER safety network is a primary search and rescue tool
covering practically all the oceans in an emergency at sea. AMVER
is a voluntary, worldwide ship reporting system involving ships
from 143 nations. Participating ships send AMVER their sailing
plans prior to departure and regular position updates throughout
their voyage.
</P>
<P>
A computer, located in Martinsburg, West Virginia, stores this
information and uses a system of dead reckoning, provides the
projected position of about 2,700 ships in every ocean of the
world each day.
</P>
<P>
Rescue planners are able to locate the area of the ocean on the
computer screen. A "surface picture" depicts the relative position
of all AMVER-participating vessels nearby, from a 50-500 mile
radius, in a pattern similar to an air traffic controller's
screen. The nearby vessels will be informed timely if an emergency
occurs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Decides to Extend Mandate of MINURSO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of the
United Nations on Friday decided to extend the mandate of the
United Nations Mission for the Referendum in Western Sahara
(MINURSO) for a further period of three months until July 20,
1998.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Council considered U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan's latest report on Western Sahara. In the report, the
U.N. chief said the the Government of Morocco and the POLISARIO have
a sharp dispute over the identifications of three tribes and there
has been a perceptible increase in the level of tension between
them.
</P>
<P>
In its resolution unanimously adopted, the Security Council
called on the two parties to comply with the agreements
reached and cooperate fully with MINURSO.
</P>
<P>
The Council also urged the two parties to solve their disputes
through dialogue as soon as possible so as to resume the
identification process.  
</P>
</TEXT>
