<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 70 Hutu Militiamen Killed in C. Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan military sources
said Friday that the army killed over 70 Hutu militiamen
Wednesday in Buringa Commune, in the country's central Gitarama
Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
"Following a tip by local residents, security forces moved in
and clashed with the militia," the Rwanda News Agency (RNA)
quoted the sources as saying. Over 70 militiamen perished in the
one-day battle, they said.
</P>
<P>
A lot of military equipment, including AK 47 and M16 assault
rifles, were captured by the Rwandan army, said the RNA. in a
special dispatch to Xinhua based in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
No casualty was given on the Rwandan army side and no civilian
was hurt in the operation.
</P>
<P>
It is said that to avoid civilian casualties, local people
evacuated the areas where the rebels had been spotted. The army
then encircled their positions before clamping down on them.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, 20 bodies of the rebels could still be seen on
the battlefield. Others were said to be in nearby forests and
swamps where it was very difficult to access immediately.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the militiamen were in military fatigues, others were
in civilian clothes and wore jungle boots," said a RNA
correspondent in Gitarama.
</P>
<P>
Old identity cards showing ethnic background of the bearers
were left on the battlefield by the running Hutu militiamen.
</P>
<P>
Abhorring the atrocities committed by the marauding militia,
some local residents expressed strong determination to support
the army in routing out trouble-makers.
</P>
<P>
"The militiamen come, they target genocide survivors, local
leaders, as well as anyone opposing them, or collaborating with
the government," one resident of Buramba told RNA.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, reports of atrocities by the fleeing
militiamen continue to emerge from neighboring communes.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday night, an unidentified number of Hutu militiamen
attacked two families in Mushubati Commune, killing 11 people.
</P>
<P>
"They came and killed the members of the two families with
hammers, and then burnt their houses," a local government
official told RNA, a private and independent news agency in
Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, mop-up operations were still going on in the
region, and more and more Hutu militiamen were killed, military
sources in Gitarama indicated.
</P>
<P>
Some of the militiamen were reportedly trying to cross back to
southern Gisenyi where they had attacked from about two months
ago. Others were running for safety in swamps and forests of
Ndiza region, re-grouping in the communes where insecurity had
heightened since late February.
</P>
<P>
For the past week alone, about 100 people had been killed in
different communes of Gitarama. Some of the victims, mainly
genocide survivors and local political leaders were hacked to
death with machetes, axes, and clubs.
</P>
<P>
While addressing a group of 1,523 former government soldiers
who had terminated solidarity camps in Nkumba Commune, in
northern Ruhengeri Prefecture Thursday, Major General Paul
Kagame, Rwandan Vice-President and Minister of Defense, strongly
condemned the continuing "genocidal acts" carried out by the very
forces behind the 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
"Criminals, those guided by ethnic ideology, those involved in
acts of destruction will never again rule Rwanda, lead Rwandans,"
Kagame underscored and appealed to Rwandans to unite against
these forces.
</P>
<P>
Major Richard Sezibera, the Rwandan army spokesman, told RNA
Friday that military operations are continuing but on low level.
</P>
<P>
"They come and they attack, but I do not think this will lead
them any further," he underlined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Shares Mixed, London Down on Profit-Taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
ended the week mixed Friday, with Paris closing higher and
Frankfurt and London finishing down, dragged lower by
profit-taking which was triggered by Asian markets' steep falls.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE-100 index of leading shares ended a lackluster
session lower for a fourth day in a row, down 79.8 points or 1.33
percent at 5,922.2, breaching the important 6,000-point level for
the first time in the month and a drop of 183.3 points from last
week.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the market was unsettled by weakness in Asian
markets and by profit-taking after a strong first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Market sentiment was also dampened by a strong pound and
renewed concern over possible interest rates rise, they added.
</P>
<P>
But some analysts said that the market's retreat this week was
a healthy enough correction after the index surged 15.5 percent
during the first quarter of this year and they expected
bargain-hunting next week.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt languished for much of the day and
closed down 55.39 points or 1.04 percent at 5,268.75 on the DAX-30
index, dragged lower by a lackluster dollar and a sharp overnight
drop on Wall Street. Equity strategists see further consolidation
next week.
</P>
<P>
However, the Paris bourse managed to close firmer, with the
CAC-40 index up 15.64 points or 0.41 percent at 3,861.58 after
having dropped nearly 1 percent earlier in the session, a fall of
32.9 points from last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that a late round of U.S.-inspired buying and
short-covering lifted the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
