<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian, British Companies Sign Gas Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian General Petroleum
Company (EGPC) and the British Gas (BG) cut a deal Saturday to set
up a joint venture to transfer and distribute natural gas to
southern Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The 220-million-U.S.-dollar deal came at the end of British
Prime Minister Tony Blair's visit to Egypt. Blair and his Egyptian
counterpart Kamal el-Ganzouri were present when the agreement was
signed by BG chief executive David Valley and EGPC chairman Abdel
Khaled Ayad.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, the two companies will jointly set up a Nile
Valley Gas Company to undertake the development of gas market and
infrastructure in southern Egypt, the Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year franchise provides for phased construction of a gas
pipeline from Cairo to Upper Egypt. The first phase will see
transmission of gas from Cairo to industrial and domestic
consumers in Beni Suef, about 120 kilometers south.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline will be extended 270 kilometers to Assuit in the
second phase and then run further southward to the governorates of
Qena and Aswan in southern Egypt in the third and fourth phases.
</P>
<P>
BG will also begin work shortly on an extensive program of
exploring for gas in the Nile Delta, north of an area where it has
already found significant reserves.
</P>
<P>
Oil Minister Hamdi el-Banbi told reporters following the
signing ceremony that the agreement is a fruit of cooperation
between the governments and businessmen of the two countries and
that Egypt has become "an oasis for Arab and foreign investment."
</P>
<P>
Also on Saturday morning, Blair and Ganzouri co-launched the
British Egyptian Business Association Council to promote
cooperation between the two countries' private sectors with
support of their governments.
</P>
<P>
Britain is Egypt's fourth largest trading partner in Europe
after Italy, France and Germany, with their annual trade volume
topping 1 billion U.S. dollars,
</P>
<P>
It is also Egypt's largest direct investor with 1 billion
sterling pounds (some 1.67 billion dollars) annually and second
largest indirect stock market investor after the U.S., according
to Ganzouri, who described his business-smart British counterpart
as a "commercial politician."
</P>
<P>
Blair later left for Riyadh, Saudi Arabia after wrapping up his
two-day visit in Cairo, the first stop of his maiden five-day tour
of the Middle East. He will also travel to Jordan, Israel and the
Palestinian self-rule areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
