<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOSOC Hosts Meeting on Global Financial Integration, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of finance,
foreign affairs and development cooperation from more than a dozen
countries met here on Saturday under the auspices of the United
Nations Economic and Social Council(ECOSOC) on global financial
integration and development.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, initiated by the United Nations General Assembly
to strengthen ECOSOC, is aimed to assess the impact of global
financial integration and to discuss ways of promoting financial
stability. This meeting is considered particularly timely in light
of recent financial disturbances in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
The theme of "global financial integration and development"
involves the strong increase in private international financial
flows to developing countries during the last years and the
proliferation in agents, types and modes of such flows, that has
brought about an unprecedented degree of financial international
interdependence.
</P>
<P>
The experience of East Asia is significant in this context
because it shows the positive contribution of financial
globalization to the development, and at the same time the risks
and challenges that it poses.
</P>
<P>
The Secretariat of UN has suggested some issues to the themes
which will be addressed in discussion. These include:
</P>
<P>
-- The national economic and financial environment: the
existence of sound macroeconomic conditions and a sound domestic
financial sector are conducive to international financial flows
and reduce the threat of financial crises.
</P>
<P>
-- Multilateral mechanisms that could monitor all national
economic policies affecting international capital flows and
regulatory arrangement to strengthen competition and the
discipline of the market on the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
-- Arrangements for the equitable sharing of the costs of
resolving financial crises.
</P>
<P>
-- ways to manage financial crises without overlooking
longer-term priorities.
</P>
<P>
At an advance press conference Thursday, ECOSOC said
participants would have a free discussion on the issues mentioned
above and no statement or conclusion is expected by the end of the
meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
