<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislation Must Reflect Views of Masses, Says NPC Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee, said recently
that legislation must conform to China's reform and development
and reflect the views of the masses.
</P>
<P>
"Legislation must adhere to the mass line and must be solidly
based on investigations and studies which emphasize the
cooperation between legislators, law practitioners and
theorists," according to Li.
</P>
<P>
The NPC chairman made the remarks during a recent inspect in
east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the process of soliciting opinions concerning the
formulation of laws also represents a process to the general
public's awareness on related issues.
</P>
<P>
"Building socialism with Chinese characteristics is a new cause
which demands exploration and summarization," said Li Peng, who
is also a member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Legislation is the primary task of the Ninth NPC and its
Standing Committee, said Li. A legal framework based on the
Constitution and socialism with Chinese characteristics has taken
shape since the initiation of the country's reform and opening
effort.
</P>
<P>
The Ninth NPC will strive to establish a socialist legal system
with Chinese characteristics by the year 2010, said Li, adding
that "we face a heavy and arduous task in terms of legislation."
</P>
<P>
Li visited Hangzhou, capital of Zhejiang Province, and
solicited opinions and suggestions from representatives from local
universities and colleges concerning the drafting of the Law on
Higher Education.
</P>
<P>
He said that competitions between countries in the 21st century
will focus on the competition related to comprehensive national
strength. The new law will be of great significance to carrying
out the program to revitalize the nation by using science and
education.
</P>
<P>
Li said the central government will continue to practice
overall management and will grant institutions of higher learning
more decision-making on their own affairs, while at the same time
encouraging nongovernmental social sectors to run schools.
</P>
<P>
Li also completed studies related to revisions of the Law on
Land Management, and expressed satisfaction with the province's
efforts in protecting arable land and wasteland reclamation.
</P>
<P>
The law, adopted in 1987, has played an important role in
protecting and developing land resources. However, new issues
concerning land management emerging in recent years require
improvements and revisions.
</P>
<P>
"We must refrain from seeking immediate and temporary economic
gains which will harm arable land resources needed for future
generations," said Li.
</P>
<P>
Li visited a number of township enterprises in suburban
Hangzhou and noted that Zhejiang is one of the pioneers in
township industrial development in China and have maintained
excellent momentum in recent years.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that township enterprises face fierce
competition in both domestic and international markets.
</P>
<P>
"Competition represents both a test and opportunities for
development," said Li, adding that the enterprises should achieve
sound growth by introducing structural readjustments,
technological upgrades and improving product quality.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng urged provincial officials to do a good job in
reforming state-owned enterprises, government institutions and the
local financial system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
