<HEADLINE> U.S. Wants Tamil Rebels to Lay Down Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States Saturday called
on  the Sri Lanka's Tamil rebels to lay down their arms and join
a peace process initiated by the Sri Lankan government to end the
15-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, visiting U.S. Ambassador
to the United Nations Bill Richardson said the U.S. was willing to
help the peace process but parties to the conflict must take the
initiative.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has declared the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
(LTTE) as a "terrorist organization." The Ambassador said the LTTE
rebels must realize that the violence will not resolve the
drawn-out conflict in the country.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been waging a war against the government
for a separate Tamil state in the north and east of the country
since 1983.
</P>
<P>
Richardson who arrived in Colombo Saturday after visiting
India, Pakistan and Afghanistan, will leave here tonight for
Bangkok. 
</P>
</TEXT>
