<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Tobacco Sales Decrease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean Tobacco
Association (ZTA) said since the beginning of the marketing
season on March 31, over 7.3 million kgs of tobacco at an average
1.33 U.S. Dollars per kg had been sold by end of the week, 10
million kgs less than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
ZTA Market Information Director Pat Davis Saturday told the
Zimbabwe News Agency that despite the devaluation of local
currency this year, prices remained low and farmers were
withholding their crop until prices firm later in the season.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The main reason for such a drop in sales is because
a lot of growers have canceled bookings or rejecting some of the
prices."
</P>
<P>
He said since the beginning of the marketing season on March
31, there had not been much improvement and competition was still
on the weak side while offerings tended to be on lower quality.
</P>
<P>
During the first 12 sale days of last year, prices averaged
2.07 U.S. Dollars per kg, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco is the country's biggest foreign currency earner. A
total of about 220 million kgs was expected to be sold this year
earning the country over 500 million U.S. Dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
