<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Summit of Americas Opens in Santiago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Leaders from 34 countries opened
their Second Summit of the Americas Saturday morning, trying to
bolster a proposed new free trade area.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was chaired by host Chilean President Eduardo Frei,
and former host U.S. President Bill Clinton spoke at the opening
of the meeting on the major achievements in the four years since
the last summit.
</P>
<P>
As well as the proposed Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA),
the participants will discuss education and other topics,
including making democracy relevant, enjoying the fruits of
freedom, building wealth through economic integration and trade,
and rejecting poverty amid growing prosperity.
</P>
<P>
After requests from Caribbean Prime Ministers, the issue of
social security will also be discussed.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the summit, President Clinton paid a two-day state
visit to Chile, and a number of bilateral agreements were reached
or signed between Chile and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The First Summit of the Americas was held in Miami in December
1994. The meeting set the goal of establishing the FTAA by 2005
and adopted a plan of action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
