<HEADLINE> Iraqi FM: Time Ripe for Lifting Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahhaf Saturday called for a lifting of sanctions against
Iraq after its compliance with U.N. resolutions, the Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi top diplomat made the appeal after talks with
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa on the developments of the
Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers exchanged views on the importance of
working at regional and international levels to for the lifting of
sanctions imposed since Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
To justify Iraq's demand for their early removal, al-Sahhaf
said his country has honored all obligations and executed all
relevant United Nations resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"Time is ripe to alleviate sufferings of the Iraqi people,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf arrived in Cairo Friday as a special envoy of Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein for talks with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
He met Mubarak earlier Saturday and conveyed a verbal message
from Saddam on progress made within the framework of a U.N.-Iraqi
deal cut in February to facilitate U.N. weapons inspections in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, a group of U.N. inspectors and senior diplomats
has inspected in March eight Iraqi presidential sites suspected of
hiding secretive weapon programs, but found nothing of this
sort. The Iraqi side was said to be cooperative during the
inspections.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf will travel on later Saturday to New York where he
will watch closely the half-yearly review within the U.N. Security
Council of a report submitted by the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) overseeing the elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi ruling Revolution Command Council on Thursday
demanded the U.N. Security Council begin proceedings for the
lifting of sanctions it takes up the issue later this month.
</P>
<P>
The seven-year-old crippling U.N. sanctions against Iraq can
only be lifted after the UNSCOM certifies that Baghdad has
scrapped all prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad said it has met all the demands, but a recent report by
the U.N. arms inspectors said Iraq had not fully accounted for
such weapons.



18/04/98 14:40 GMT

NNNN
22:48 22:48 g # PAB
</P>
