<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM Stresses to Alleviate Social Impact of Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
said Saturday afternoon that his government will find ways to
mitigate the social impact of the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
At the 52th annual congress of the ruling Democrat Party, Chuan
said the government will not neglect unemployment, poverty and
other social problems when tackling economic woes.
</P>
<P>
The government has taken measures to alleviate the liquidity
crunch of local enterprises and promote exports, which are all
conducive to the mitigation of social problems, Chuan said at the
one-day congress.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund has predicted that the number
of jobless people in Thailand could reach 2 million by the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
In view of this, Chuan said that a committee headed by himself
was set up to alleviate the mounting pressure of unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Chuan recalled the situation when his government took office
last November, saying his cabinet was confronted with the most
serious economic downturn in Thai history.
</P>
<P>
Five months later, confidence has been partly rebuilt on the
Thai economy when the baht returned from fluctuation to stability
and the capital inflows overwhelmed the outflows, the Prime
Minister, who is the leader of Democrat Party, noted.
</P>
<P>
Though a long and hard way ahead, Chuan said he is confident
that the government will solve problems both economic and social.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from across the country took part in Saturday's
congress.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1946, the Democrat Party is the oldest political
party in Thailand and the second largest party at present with 123
seats in the National Assembly. It is also the core party of the
ruling coalition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Calls for National Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe Saturday urged the nation to be united with a common
vision and purpose as it moves towards the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
He made the call while addressing thousands of people who
crowed the National Sports Stadium here to mark the 18th
anniversary of Zimbabwe's independence from Britain.
</P>
<P>
"We should all pull together in one direction with a shared
vision, a unity of purpose and common values of patriotism,
selflessness and hard work," he said.
</P>
<P>
He deplored violence, saying only through unity could the
aspirations of the Zimbabwean people be attained.
</P>
<P>
"Whereas it is a democratic right for aggrieved persons to
peacefully demonstrate, the tendency towards a culture of violent
demonstrations and lawlessness must stop, must stop, must stop,"
Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
He assured the Zimbabweans that the government would not allow
a situation of anarchy to develop.
</P>
<P>
On the national economy, he said that the country's economy
had over the years experienced some rather sharp shocks, notably
the depreciation of the Zimbabwean Dollar by 20 percent as at the
end of December 1997, the high price rises and the galloping
inflation causing in turn a push-up of interest rates.
</P>
<P>
At the same time high consumer prices had the effect of
reducing real wages quite drastically.
</P>
<P>
As a result, he said, the government was compelled by the
ensuing circumstances to resort to several measures to encounter
the adverse effects on economy.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the GDP growth rate declined to 3.7 percent from 8.1
percent realized in 1996, and economic performance is expected to
further slow down this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Turning to sectoral performance, Mugabe said that the 1996/97
agricultural season had recorded a growth rate of 21.4 percent,
but prospects for 1997/98 production indicate that the sector
can't, because of erratic rains, perform as last year.
</P>
<P>
In the education and health sectors, he said, commissions of
enquiry had been put in place to review their operations which
had been facing various problems.
</P>
<P>
This year's celebrations were characterized by the traditional
lighting of the independence flame, mass displays, parachute
displays and police displays.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
