<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volunteers Demolish the "Great Wall of Garbage" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, April 18 (Xinhua) -- A garbage invasion to the Great
Wall of China met a major counter-attack by a multi-national joint
force today at the Wall's Jinshanling section.
</P>
<P>
The 120-strong army consisted of volunteers from about 20
countries including China, Britain, the United States and
Bangladesh, each armed with a pair of cotton gloves and a huge
plastic trash bag.
</P>
<P>
Beijing urbanites, foreign experts, and tourists picked up and
bagged away over half a ton of food wraps, beer bottles, coke
cans, film boxes and all kinds of paper on and off the
Jinshanling, one of the most-visited section of the Wall at the
border of Beijing and Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Litterings, no less severe than in other tourist spots of
China, forms two parallel walls of garbage along the fractions of
the Great Wall opened to tourists, hence tarnishing its look.
</P>
<P>
It also astonished William Lindesay, a British expert who has
built a career as Great Wall adventurist and researcher in
Beijing. He called up today's campaign helped by five-star Great
Wall Sheraton Hotel and named it "I cleaned the Great Wall."
</P>
<P>
"The idea came when my friends suggested me not to mention in
my book many wild and clean parts of the Wall I have visited, in
fear of that the publicity would attract people there to spoil
them," Lindesay says. "This makes me be aware how serious the
situation is."
</P>
<P>
Braving thorny bushes and foot skids, a quick-handed Chinese
student from Qinghua University easily filled his huge plastic bag
in less than 20 minutes. The 19-year-old Hu Jingnan rubbed a
scratch on the arm and said, "The littering is worse than I
thought, we should really think of some means to stop people doing
that."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volunteers Demolish the "Great Wall of Garbage" (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The volunteers' work at least forestalled today any littering
at Jinshanling, where tourists were happy to dump their picnic
disposals directly into a passing volunteer's black plastic
bag. "I think the problem is that you don't see trash bins around
here," one complained.
</P>
<P>
"Bring it home," is the solution suggested by
environment-conscious persons.
</P>
<P>
Graeme Allen from Sheraton Hotel was keen to notice that the
Wall itself was clean, but garbage was all around off the its two
sides. "People has respect for the Wall, but don't care about
environment," he rationalized.
</P>
<P>
Volunteers' assault to garbage lasted for three hours in the
mid-day sunlight. The organizer William Lindesay refrained from a
sigh of relief at the end, "It's much cleaner, but we have made
only a tiny impression on a major problem."
</P>
<P>
All the foreigners in the group were anxious to show they
weren't trying to teach the owner of the Great Wall how to take
care of it. Spotting 20 elite-brand champagne bottles excited
them. Priced nearly an equivalent of 100 U.S. dollars in local
market, the bubbling wine was clearly not consumed by Chinese.
</P>
<P>
"The Great Wall is a pride of all people in the world, not only
the Chinese," said Salie Beaumont from Britain. "Everybody should
learn to protect it."
</P>
<P>
When the group were posing for triumphant photo-takings before a
three-hour bus ride back to Beijing, the general manager of
Jinshanling Park showed up in grey suit. He looked thankful, and
nodded vehemently at William Lindesay's suggestion of printing
some love-the-environment notice on the admission tickets he sells
to the 100,000 visitors coming every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pol Pot's Body Cremated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The body of Pol Pot, former
leader of the Khmer Rouge, was cremated Saturday in a northern
Cambodian village three kilometers from the Thai border.
</P>
<P>
Local television showed that the body was put in a wooden
coffin, which was set alight when the simple ceremony began at
about 9:30 a.m. (0230 GMT) Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that about 20 Khmer Rouge soldiers attended the
cremation, which was held just outside the cottage where Pol pot
died of heart attack late Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The Khmer Rouge has decided to scatter the ash of Pol pot to
three spots in the northern area of Cambodia, reports said.
</P>
</TEXT>
