<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hashimoto, Yeltsin Hold First Round of Summit Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Russian President Boris
Yeltsin and Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto held their
first round of informal talks Saturday to discuss ways to promote
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
At the first of two "no-necktie" talks at Japan's seaside
resort of Kawana, about 130 kilometers southwest of Tokyo, the two
leaders agreed on reciprocal visits by Hashimoto to Moscow this
fall and by Yeltsin to Tokyo next year.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who arrived earlier in the day at Tokyo's Haneda
airport and immediately flew by helicopter to Kawana, was quoted
as telling Hashimoto that he wants to promote ties on both the
economic and political fronts through a series of vigorous
political exchanges.
</P>
<P>
During the 90-minute talks, the two leaders reviewed economic
cooperation called for under the so-called "Hashimoto-Yeltsin
Plan" adopted last November at their previous informal summit in
Krasnoyarsk, eastern Siberia.
</P>
<P>
With the aim of giving further momentum to the plan, Hashimoto
told Yeltsin that Japan will disburse 600 million U.S. dollars in
untied loans through the Export-Import Bank of Japan to help
Russia develop natural resources.
</P>
<P>
This is part of a 1.5 billion dollar credit line Japan offered
to Moscow in February for resources development over the next two
years.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also agreed that Japan and Russia will cooperate in
combating global warming by jointly attaining the targets on
carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions set at last December's United
Nations climate conference in Kyoto.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders, however, left the main task of their talks --
resolving a territorial row so that a treaty to formally their
Second World War hostilities can be signed by 2000 -- to Sunday's
second round of talks.
</P>
<P>
In Saturday's talks, Yeltsin proposed that Moscow and Tokyo
jointly build facilities for processing marine products and needed
infrastructure such as roads and ports on a chain of disputed
islands off Japan's northernmost main island of Hokkaido.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, obviously aware that Japan's acceptance of the
proposal could give Moscow an advantage in negotiations for a
peace treaty, replied that Tokyo wants to "consider" the proposal
"in parallel with negotiations for a peace treaty."
</P>
<P>
The dispute over ownership of the four Russian-held islands --
Etorofu, Kunashiri, Shikotan and the Habomai group -- has
prevented Japan and Russia from signing a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
At their informal summit last November in the eastern Siberian
city of Krasnoyarsk, Hashimoto and Yeltsin agreed that they would
strive to conclude a peace treaty by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's visit, which was originally scheduled for April 11-13
and delayed one week due to Russia's domestic political
uncertainty, is his first since 1993 when he made an official
visit to Tokyo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
