<HEADLINE> Beijing Assists Laid-off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Yan Changcheng, a laid-off
Beijinger unable to find a job for some two years, will go to work
at the Beijing Union Medical College Hospital on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Yan is amongst the first group of people benefitting from the
first employment assistance program initiated today by the local
government.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has formulated the program to provide
assistance for an estimated 190,000 laid-off workers. The program,
the first of its kind in the nation, offers free services to help
people find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Yan, 35, who formerly worked for the Beijing Electrical
Machinery Plant, will earn 500 yuan (60 US dollars) per month for
working in the hospital's laundry department.
</P>
<P>
"The opportunity is precious and I will do my best at the new
job." said Yan.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Labor Bureau joined 18 district branches in
organizing a recent employment fair which attracted the interest
of over 34,000 laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
However, some laid-off workers prefer to accept 200 yuan
bottom-line monthly relief from the government rather than accept
what they consider to be demeaning jobs.
</P>
<P>
The bureau plans to organize another large-scale employment
assistance program later this year, in addition to offering grass
roots employment information services for workers, according to
Labor Bureau Director You Lantian.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities will create at least 190,000 job
opportunities for laid-off workers, according to You.  
</P>
</TEXT>
