<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Hails Taliban's Readiness to Cease Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Iran Saturday voiced welcome to
the readiness of the Afghan Taliban group to cease fire, calling
it a "positive" step to restore peace in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
If the Taliban group accepts a cease-fire and holds talks
with the Northern Alliance, "it will be a positive change" in
Afghanistan, Iran's Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi
said.
</P>
<P>
During a recent visit to Kabul by the United States Ambassador
to the U.N. Bill Richardson, the Taliban group promised to cease
fire by April 27.
</P>
<P>
According to Richardson, the Afghan Northern Alliance has also
agreed to a truce and hold talks with the Taliban group before
April 27.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been calling for a cease-fire and talks among the
Afghan groups, the spokesman said, reiterating Tehran's readiness
to help solve the Afghan crisis under the sponsorship of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Along with Richardson's mission, the U.N. special envoy for
Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi stepped up his efforts to help end the
war in the country through talks with leaders of Afghan neighbors.
</P>
<P>
During his visit here, Brahimi called on Iranian leaders to
make more efforts to coordinate with the U.N., the Organization of
the Islamic Conference and regional countries to seek ways of
restoring peace in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Islamic Taliban regime came to power after its armed
forces captured the capital of Kabul in September, 1996. It drove
out the government troops led by President Burhanuddin Rabbani,
leader the alliance of Guerrillas who stormed into the capital in
1992 after years of war with then Soviet-backed regime.
</P>
<P>
Ever since, a new civil war has been continuing between the
Taliban forces, which control most parts of the country, and the
guerrilla alliance which occupies the north.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Iran's special envoy for Afghan
affairs Alaeddin Boroujerdi is currently visiting Moscow to
coordinate with Russian officials on the efforts by the U.N. and
the U.S. over the Afghan issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
