<HEADLINE> Mozambique Signs Pact With Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique Friday signed an
inter-governmental agreement with the African Advanced Level
Telecommunications Institute based in Nairobi, becoming the ninth
member of the regional institute.
</P>
<P>
The organization teaches telecommunications knowledge to
management personnel from countries within the eastern and
southern Africa region, local media reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique's Ambassador to Kenya, Francisco Gigaro, when
signing the pact, said his government is committed to working
together with other countries in acquiring knowledge on modern
information technology.
</P>
<P>
"This agreement formalizes my government's acceptance of the
institute and adherence to the family of African countries
committed in harmonizing telecommunications systems in the
continent," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Foreign Minister Bonaya Godana welcomed the move, saying
the training is important to the region in view of the globe's
rapid technological advancement.
</P>
<P>
High level training of telecommunications personnel is of
critical importance to the region, more so as telecommunications
and other information technologies had become critical in today's
world, he said.
</P>
<P>
He called for the regional governments to help the institute
to formulate appropriate and cost-effective solutions to common
telecommunications challenges.
</P>
<P>
Godana asked benefactors to continue supporting the institute
financially to facilitate its smooth and effective operations.
</P>
<P>
The institute which started in Nairobi in 1987 as a project of
the U.N. Development Program (UNDP) is executed by the
International Telecommunications Union.  
</P>
</TEXT>
