<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Russian Duma Refuses Kiriyenko Second Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government crisis
deepened when the State Duma (lower house of parliament) failed to
approve Sergei Kiriyenko as prime minister for the second time.
</P>
<P>
On Friday the Duma deputies turned down the president's nominee
with 115 voting for, 271 against and 11 abstentions. The result
was worse for Kiriyenko than the first vote on April 10 when 143
voted for and 186 against in a secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
Under Russia's constitution, the premier's candicacy needs at
least 226 votes in the 450-seat Duma to be confirmed. If the
nomination is rejected a third time, the president has the right
to dissolve the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, as he had vowed, immediately resubmitted Kiriyenko's
name for a third vote expected to be held on April 24.
</P>
<P>
The president, who left Friday night for an informal summit
with Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto in Kawana, Japan,
appeared to be "calm," confidently believing that Kiriyenko would
be approved by the Duma in the end.
</P>
<P>
"We expect the third vote to bring about the result the country
needs -- an approval of Kiriyenko's nomination," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party, which dominates the Duma with 135 seats,
pressed successfully for a roll-call vote in the second try on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov announced Wednesday that all
the Communist deputies in parliament's lower house were bound by
party discipline to oppose Kiriyenko when his nomination came up
on the second attempt on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the ballot, 121 Communist deputies voted against and only
two for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
However, the Communists appeared to be divided before the
second vote when house speaker Gennady Seleznyov, a member of the
Communist Party group, called for the approval of Kiriyenko as
premier, saying that he would fight to preserve the State Duma.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government's crisis began on March 23, when Yeltsin
sacked former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and the whole
government, and chose 35-year-old Kiriyenko, the Fuel and Energy
Minister as acting prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition argument against 35-year-old Kiriyenko is
that he is too young and inexperienced. Formerly a little-known
local banker, he has less than a year's experience in government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
