<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM Calls for Speeding Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina Saturday called on agricultural researchers to make
innovative work to bring the crop production system up to a modern
standard that keeps pace with the changeable climate and weather,
the national news agency BSS reported.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister made the call while addressing a meeting of
Bangladesh Agricultural University Saturday morning in Mymensingh,
118 kilometers north of the capital.
</P>
<P>
She expressed the hope that the university would take up more
research activities in order to innovate and improve the species
of economically important crops.
</P>
<P>
"Any technology we develop or propagate must be compatible with
the country's agro-ecological and socio-economic factors," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The government wanted to strengthen agricultural education and
research with a view to making the present trend of development
more dynamic, she stated.
</P>
<P>
"A new struggle lies before us to ensure food security to our
people," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
She called for planned utilization of all potentials of
agriculture for growth of the economy and national food security,
referring to the thrust of the plan on poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
"We want to face the problem through generation of productive
employment, attainment of self-reliance in food, planned
population control, strengthening technological base and
establishing social justice," she said.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture accounts for about one-third of the GDP and
employs about two-thirds of the labor force in Bangladesh. It has
been playing a dominant role in the process of the country's
economic growth, and "this trend will continue" in the future, she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
