<HEADLINE> HK To Adopt New Measures To tackle Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government will
launch a number of new initiatives to help the unemployed re-enter
the labor market.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the meeting of the Inter-bureau and departmental
Working Group on employment Friday, Joseph W P Wong, secretary
for Education and Manpower, said: "we will soon be launching two
new initiatives to help the unemployed."
</P>
<P>
Firstly, he said that the Employees Retraining Board will be
running special tailor-made on-the-job retraining programs for
employers on top of its existing courses.
</P>
<P>
The primary objective of such training programs is to equip the
unemployed trainees with new and transferable skills which will
enable them to secure a job, hold down their jobs in the labor
market and upgrade their skills in the longer term.
</P>
<P>
The second initiative is that the Vocational Training Council
will be launching a Business Starter program targeted at middle
managers who become unemployed and wish to explore the option of
starting their own business.
</P>
<P>
The program aims at providing potential owner-managers with the
knowledge and skills to evaluate their business plans, conduct
feasibility studies and set up new business in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Wong said the government has been implementing a
series of measures in conjunction with the Hong Kong Tourist
Association (HKTA) to enhance the competitiveness of its tourist
industry.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the HKTA is launching a large-scale new promotion
campaign, costing 173 million HK dollars (22 million
U.S. dollars), to promote Hong Kong in the international tourist
market so as to create more employment chances for the employed.
</P>
<P>
Wong said that the economic fundamentals of Hong Kong remain
strong and employment prospects still very positive in the medium
to long term.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to work closely with employers, employees and
training bodies to monitor the effectiveness of the measures and
to explore even better measures," Wong emphasized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
