<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Hotels Adjust Policies for Low Arrivals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Major Bangkok hotels, suffering
from a significant drop in Japanese arrivals in the first quarter,
have to review policies with a shift of focus to individual
travelers.
</P>
<P>
The shift would compensate for the decline in the number of
group and family visitors, said Masao Wakuta, general manager of
Nikko Mahanakorn Bangkok, a five-star hotel.
</P>
<P>
A TV report on Saturday quoted Masao as saying that the
first-quarter arrivals were at least 15 percent less than in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In the past 12 months, overall Japanese arrivals dropped 20
percent, as a result of the region's economic turmoil, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
A number of hotels such as Nikko Mahanakorn, Shangri-La, Regent
and Hotel Sunroute have begun adjusting their market strategies,
putting into effect additional promotion campaigns and greater use
of direct marketing. They would also have to create more
diversified travel packages to lure visitors.
</P>
<P>
The packages would include inbound round-trip tickets which
were expected to draw some individual travelers from Japan, as
they are more flexible in their travel and normally wound not
limit their stay in one particular place, Wakuta said.
</P>
<P>
He said hotels would have to maintain their service levels,
along with value-added quality to sustain a longer stay, as well
as induce return visits.
</P>
<P>
A further decline in Japanese arrivals in Thailand was expected
to continue from this second quarter until early October,
according to the report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
