<HEADLINE> HK Employees' Average Income Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The average labor earnings for
all the major sectors in Hong Kong recorded an increase of 9.18
percent in the fourth quarter of 1997 over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
After discounting changes in consumer prices, there was an
increase of 3.8 percent in real terms, the latest figures released
by the Census and Statistics Department show.
</P>
<P>
Average payroll per person engaged in the financing, insurance,
real estate and business services sectors recorded an increase of
12.3 percent in nominal terms or 6.8 percent in real terms.
</P>
<P>
Varying increases in average labor earnings also registered in
the sectors of manufacturing, wholesale, retail and import and
export trades, restaurants and hotels, transport, storage and
communications.
</P>
<P>
As for the community, social and personal services sector,
average payroll per person engaged had an increase of 11.1 percent
in nominal terms or 5.7 percent in real terms.
</P>
<P>
A government secretariat spokesman noted that the increases in
earnings in most of the major sectors continued to be significant
in the fourth quarter of 1997. This was notwithstanding the
adverse effects of the regional financial turmoil already
spreading over. 
</P>
</TEXT>
