<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Pledges Support to Egypt in Fighting Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said Saturday Britain would soon introduce stronger anti-terrorism
laws and will stand by Egypt in fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Blair, who arrived here Friday afternoon, told the
British-Egyptian Business Association (BEBA) over a working
breakfast that Britain, the current chairman of the European
Union, will continue to promote "a just and sustainable settlement
of the Arab-Israeli dispute."
</P>
<P>
Blair, extending his condolences and sympathy for the families
of those murdered by terrorists in Luxor last November, said "This
tragic and horrific attack was carried out by terrorists trying to
strike a blow against the Egyptian government."
</P>
<P>
Altogether 58 foreign tourists, including six Britons, were
massacred in the southern Egyptian archeological city by six
Muslim militants, in the most violent attack of a six-year
insurgency against Egypt's secular government.
</P>
<P>
"I told President (Hosni) Mubarak that Britain stands shoulder
to shoulder with Egypt in its determination to fight terrorism
from wherever it comes. Britain will not be a safe haven for
terrorists. We will bring forward proposals soon for stronger
counter-terrorism laws in the U.K.," said Blair.
</P>
<P>
The British prime minister held 150-minute talks with Mubarak
Friday evening with focus on the European role to break the
year-long deadlock in the Mideast peace process. Both leaders
warned of grave consequences of the peace drive failed to move
forward.
</P>
<P>
Turning to economics, Blair said he shared with Mubarak an
important conviction that sability and the prospects for peace are
inextricably linked to a prosperous and economically open Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
"People, both Arab and Israeli, need to realize that by working
together in the economic sphere -- trading, investing in each
other's companies -- they will not only be better off, but will
also help bring about a long term peace," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been frozen since
march 1997. The EU, the largest donor country to the Palestinians,
hopes to propel its political influence in the region.
</P>
<P>
Also on Saturday morning, Blair and Egyptian Prime Minister
Kamal el-Ganzouri co-launched the BEBA Council to promote
cooperation between private sectors of the two countries with the
support of their governments.
</P>
<P>
The occasion was attended by around 200 diplomats and business
leaders of the two countries, including Egyptian Minister of
Public Enterprise Atef Obeid and Presidential Advisor Osama el-Baz.
</P>
<P>
With annual trade volume topping 1 billion U.S. dollars,
Britain is Egypt's fourth largest trade partner in Europe after
Italy, France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
U.K. is also Egypt's largest direct investor with 1 billion
sterling pounds (1.67 billion dollars) annually and second largest
indirect stock market investor after the U.S., according to
Ganzouri, who described his business-smart British counterpart as
a "commercial politician."
</P>
<P>
Before winding up his two-day visit in Cairo Saturday
afternoon, Blair and Egyptian Minister of Oil Hamdi Banbi will
attend the signing ceremony of a contract granting British Gas
Company for supplying the Southern Valley with natural gas.
</P>
<P>
Blair will visit Saudi Arabia, Jordan, Israel and the
Palestinian National Authority on his maiden five-day tour of the
Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
