<HEADLINE> French Ex-Defense Minister Creates New Right-wing Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Former French Defense Minister
Charles Millon created a new right-wing party Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the creation of the party at a rally of his
supporters in Lyon, Millon said that the new party, which is
simply called "La Droite (the Right)", is "a national movement of
political action" aimed at renewing the political life of France.
</P>
<P>
Millon was expelled by the centrist Union for French Democracy
earlier this month, because he accepted the votes from the
extreme-right party of the National Front during an election in
March in Rhone-Alpes.
</P>
<P>
He was re-elected the regional council president of Rhone-Alpes.
</P>
<P>
One of his nine vice-presidents of the regional council is
Alain Merieux, an entrepreneur of the Gaullist Rally for the
Republic (RPR), who is a close friend of President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
The RPR said that Merieux will be expelled from the party if he
does not quit the post. 
</P>
