<HEADLINE> Mubarak Gets Message From Saddam on Arms Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
received Saturday a message from Iraqi President Saddam Hussein on
the progress made within the agreement between Iraq and the United
Nations on arms inspection.
</P>
<P>
The message was conveyed by Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed Al-Sahhaf who arrived here Friday for talks with Mubarak and
Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from his meeting with the Egyptian leader Saturday
morning, Sahhaf said that he came to Egypt as Saddam's special
envoy to convey a verbal message to Mubarak, focusing on the
February memo of understanding struck by Baghdad and the U.N.
</P>
<P>
"The message also centered on the result achieved so far and
the steps expected to be taken in the near future," Sahaf said,
adding that he received a "full-fledged" response to the message
from Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa together with Iraqi
delegation to the Arab League Nabil Nejm attended the talks.
</P>
<P>
During the recent Iraqi-U.N. standoff on arms inspection of
Iraqi presidential sites, Sahaf visited Egypt in February within a
tour of a number of Arab countries to hand over messages to their
leaders from Saddam.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister later Saturday will travel on to New York
where he will watch closely the half-yearly review within the
U.N. Security Council of a report submitted by the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) overseeing the elimination of Iraq's weapons
of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf will meet representatives of some members of the
Security Council to discuss the latest development in Iraq's
relationship with the U.N..
</P>
<P>
The seven-year-old crippling U.N. sanctions against Iraq can
only be lifted after the UNSCOM certifies that Baghdad has scrapped
all prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, New York times quoted Friday UNSCOM chief inspector
Richard Butler as warning that Iraq has not yet inched towards
meeting the conditions required for lifting U.N. sanctions imposed
since its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
After a six-month standoff with Iraq, the U.N. inspectors,
accompanied by veteran diplomats from the U.N. Security Council
member states, inspected in March eight Iraqi presidential sites
which Iraq had previously declared off-limits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
