<HEADLINE> Mozambique's Municipal Elections to Be Held as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique's local elections
would be held as planned, despite some opposition parties decided
to boycott the elections, a senior Mozambican official said here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Leonardo Simbine, Chairman of the Commission of National
Election, was quoted by Noticias as saying that it is "their
legal right to give up their right in the elections, which should
be respected", and what also deserves respect is the right to
take part in the election for other parties.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambique Liberation Front (Frelimo), Democratic Union
(UD) and 11 other organizations have registered for the
elections.
</P>
<P>
About 16 other parties, including the biggest opposition
party, the National Resistance Movement of Mozambique (Renamo),
have not registered for the elections by the April 16 deadline
for registration.
</P>
<P>
These parties have made it clear that they will not to take
part in the elections on the pretext of the lack of technical or
economic conditions for the municipal elections slated for june
30 in 33 towns and cities.
</P>
<P>
Afonso Dhlakama, Chairman of Renamo said Friday that if
Frelimo agrees to take the Renamo and other opposition parties
into the Technical Secretariat of the Election Administration
which will be in charge of the election process, they would
change their stance for the elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
