<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Work on 2nd Line Station of Guangzhou Subway to Start in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, will start building an key station on
the second line of the city's subway network in July.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou Subway Corporation will start a bidding for the
project beginning from April 20 for the construction of the Haizhu
Square Station, and the project will cover a 2,311-meter section
on an experiment basis that runs through beneath the Pearl River.
</P>
<P>
The project is considered the most difficult undertaking in
terms of technology in the entire second subway line construction,
according to Wang Wenbin, deputy general manager of the company.
</P>
<P>
For the first-phase construction, the north-south second subway
line will be 21.34 km long, and half of it will use light rails,
costing about 10 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Workers will have to build one car-exchange center, 19
stations, including nine stations and ten flyover stations for the
projected subway line.
</P>
<P>
The second subway line will join the first soon after it ends
in traversing beneath the Pearl River.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary plan calls for completion and operation of the
second subway line in 2000, and passenger volume will amount to
32,800 per hour during rush hours in the early months of the
subway operations.
</P>
<P>
The experimental section, which is still waiting for a
governmental approval, will take three years to complete and will
cost 640 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The city's first 18.5-km subway line is still under
construction and is expected to be fully completed in July this
year. A 5.4-km section of the line went on trial operation last
June and construction of its 11 stations has been going on
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The first subway line was started in December 1993, and it is
expected to cost 13.8 billion yuan. Most of the equipment used in
the metro subway network was imported and funds came from the
German, US, British, and Japanese governments. Part of the cost
was covered by loans from international banks or raised through
real estate deals in areas along the subway line.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou is now China's fourth city with a subway network,
after Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
