<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Airways to Modify All Its Boeing 737s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 18 (Xinhua) -- South African Airways (SAA)
will comply with a United States Federal Aviation Administration
(FAA) directive that all Boeing 737s be rewired to prevent
potential short circuits that could spark fuel-tank explosions.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Saturday Star quoted SAA public relations officer
Jackie Rakitla as saying that the corporation's 11 aircraft would
be rewired as soon as it received communication from the FAA.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the FAA directive especially recommended
better insulation for all wires and that low-voltage and
high-voltage wires that are currently bundled together be rewired
sparately to prevent arcs between them.
</P>
<P>
It also called for more fire avoidance systems and recommended
that new pressure-reducing valves be installed in ventilation
systems for fuel tanks and ducts to stop fires from spreading.
</P>
<P>
The modification will cost an estimated 180,000 Rand (36,000
U.S. Dollars) to rewire each plane and SAA might end up with a
two-million Rand (400,000 U.S. Dollars) bill for the
modification.
</P>
<P>
The FAA has allowed 12 months for airlines to implement the
modifications. Similar directives were issued in November last
year for Boeing 747-100s, 200s and 300s, the older version of the
jumbo jet, following the investigation into the cause of the July
1996 crash of TWA flight 800 off the coast of New York.  
</P>
</TEXT>
