<HEADLINE> Investments Surge in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Despite the currency crisis,
investments soared by 25.5 percent to 99 billion pesos (2.6
billion U.S. dollars) in the Philippines in the first quarter of
1998 from the same period last year, according to the Board of
Investments (BOI).
</P>
<P>
In a report published Saturday, the BOI of the Department of
Trade and Industry said that of the total registered investments,
equity investments went up by more than 30 percent to 16.7 billion
pesos (44 million dollars) from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar Bautista was quoted saying
Friday the performance show investors are confident in pushing
ahead with their business plans given the country's strong
economic fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
For this year, the BOI is targeting 700 billion pesos (18.4
billion dollars) total national investments.
</P>
<P>
For the first quarter this year, a total of 78 new and
expansion projects were registered with the BOI.
</P>
<P>
Projects in power generation led the field with 57 billion
pesos (1.5 billion dollars) worth of investments or 58 percent of
the total. Cement projects followed with 16.7 billion pesos (44
million dollars) in fresh investments. 
