<HEADLINE> Two More Philippine Natives Die of Food Poisoning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MANILA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Two more hungry Tiruray natives,
who resorted to eating "kayos," a wild root crop abundant in the
southern province of Maguindanao, recently died of food poisoning,
bringing the death toll to 14.
</P>
<P>
In a communique addressed to Health Secretary Carmencita
Reodica on Saturday, the Integrated Provincial Health Office
identified the latest fatalities as sisters Mercy and Lilet
Dalimbang, aged three and one, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The deaths of the Dalimbang kids came in the midst of
government efforts to distribute relief goods to poor families
heavily affected by the drought-induced El Nino phenomenon in
Maguindanao.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the health office reported 12 others
natives, two from North Upi and ten from South Upi, who also died
from eating "kayos" in the province.
</P>
<P>
Maguindanao health chief Tahir Sulaik said the "kayos" was
found out to contain dioscorine, a substance proven fatal to
humans at a certain level.
</P>
<P>
Sulaik, who visited the adjoining towns of Upi earlier this
week together with health Undersecretary Antonio Lopez, has
recommended to Reodica to immediately send more relief items and
mobilize action teams in the area to address the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
