<HEADLINE> Kenya's Opposition Lobby Group Drops Mass Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's main opposition group
National Convention Executive Council (NCEC) has withdrawn its
program of mass action to enable the constitutional review
process to take root in the country.
</P>
<P>
The group said Friday that it is committed to dialogue to
bring changes in the country and urged the government to take the
"olive branch".
</P>
<P>
"As an act of good faith, the NCEC has withdrawn the program
of mass action in Nairobi to give the unfolding work on
consensus building on constitution change," co-convener Kibutha
Kibwana said.
</P>
<P>
"We want to send a loud message to the country that the NCEC
will not obstruct a bona fide and genuine process of
constitutional reform," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mass action began with a planned nationwide strike on April 3,
which flopped after most Kenyans ignored it. Subsequent strikes
were designed to be staged on May 4 and 5, in June and July.
</P>
<P>
However, Kibwana said it was not the abortive strike that made
the lobby to withdraw the program.
</P>
<P>
The NCEC wishes to be included in the "facilitative"
Inter-Party parliamentary Committee meeting set for May 11, which
will draw up modalities on how a Constitutional Review
Commission will work, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that it will be unreasonable for them to seek
inclusion in the committee and at the same time mobilize Kenyans
for mass action.
</P>
<P>
"We want to build this country together. What is critical now
is for us to create an environment where everyone comes in...It
is logical for the government to include the NCEC and all
stakeholders in the level-one meeting," he added. 
</P>
