<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: No Winner in Possible Duma's Dissolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Russia will have to carry on
without a government for another week since the lower house State
Duma turned down President Boris Yeltsin's choice of Sergei
Kiriyenko as prime minister in the second vote Friday.
</P>
<P>
It is however too early to forecast a rupture between the
president and the parliament, which may trigger early elections
and political conflict.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko lost his second confirmation when 271 voted against
him, 85 more than that in the initial round. Consenting votes fell
from 143 to 115, with 11 abstentions at Friday's Duma ballot.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko won backing from the pro-government Our Home Is
Russia (NDR) and the Russia's Region blocs but was rebuffed by the
Communists, the Liberal Democratic Party and the Yabloko bloc.
</P>
<P>
Although Kiriyenko received an even less favorable result in
the second round, he still has got another but the last chance,
when Yeltsin renominated Kiriyenko for premiership immediately
after the voting. The third and final round of confirmation voting
is scheduled for next week.
</P>
<P>
Under the Russian constitution, Yeltsin must dissolve the State
Duma and call early elections if the lower house rejects the
president's prime minister nomination for a third time.
</P>
<P>
However, the dissolution of the Duma spells doom for Yeltsin's
plan of realizing social stability and economic revival. Yeltsin
moreover would be reluctant to call for early elections for fear
he might have to deal with even a tougher State Duma three months
later.
</P>
<P>
For the leftist-dominated Duma, early dissolution will disrupt
the strategic plans of all the political parties for the next
presidential elections. It also means many deputies will have to
leave the legislature.
</P>
<P>
Well aware that dissolving the present Duma could cost both
sides a high price, Yeltsin and the Duma are making harder
"bargains" before the "showdown" in the final vote.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has convened the opposition-proposed round-table meeting
and promised to solve the welfare problems of the deputy
members. Catering to the Duma's demand, the president also
announced he will not seek a third term of office in the next
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Yeltsin on Tuesday, the Duma's Communist
speaker Gennady Seleznyov called on the lower house to approve
Kiriyenko's nomination "so that the term of the incumbent Duma can
be fulfilled."
</P>
<P>
Perceived as a show of flexibility in the Duma, a handful of
leftist opposition members supported Kiriyenko's nomination in
both rounds. Two Communist deputies voted for Kiriyenko in
the second open voting, along with five deputies from Power
to People and four from Agrarian blocs.
</P>
<P>
The Duma speaker Seleznyov did not attend the ballot.
</P>
<P>
For all the bargaining surrounding the premier designate, it is
becoming increasingly obvious that all parties wish to readjust
their standings so as to avoid the dissolution of the Duma, which
would be the choice if they fail to work out a solution to the
wide gap between their demands.
</P>
<P>
As the final round of voting approaches, whether the political
forces are heading toward compromise or conflict remains to be
seen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian President Arrives in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
arrived here on Saturday for a two-day informal summit with
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto to promote broader
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
After arriving at Tokyo's Haneda airport, Yeltsin was
immediately whisked off to a helicopter which will take him to the
site for the summit, a resort villa in the town of Kawana,
Shizuoka Prefecture, about 130 kilometers southwest of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
At the Kawana seaside resort, Yeltsin and Hashimoto will spend
24 hours in a relaxed "no-neckties" mood, with two rounds of
summit talks scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Hashimoto will hold a first 90-minute round of
summit talks late Saturday afternoon to discuss ways to promote
bilateral ties in a wide range of fields.
</P>
<P>
The agenda at the informal summit will include a review of the
so-called Hashimoto-Yeltsin plan, adopted at last November's
informal summit talks in the Siberian city of Krasnoyarsk,
security dialogue and cultural exchange, Japanese government
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The focus of the summit talks will be how Hashimoto and Yeltsin
can move forward bilateral negotiations so that a peace treaty may
be signed by the year 2000, they said.
</P>
<P>
Japan and Russia have not signed a peace treaty due to the
decades-old dispute over the ownership of four Russian-held
islands off Japan's northernmost main island of Hokkaido.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto and Yeltsin are also expected to discuss how to form
a framework for four-party security dialogue among Japan, Russia,
China and the United States, government sources said.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Yeltsin and Hashimoto are scheduled to hold their
second round of summit talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
