<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inter-Korean Talks Ends Fruitless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The first inter-Korean high-level
talks in four years ended here today after a week-long fruitless
negotiations, and no timetable is in sight for further talks.
</P>
<P>
The gap between the two sides remains unchanged: the North
wants the fertilizer aid first, while the South insists on that
the North fixes a date for talks on the issue of reunion of
separated families.
</P>
<P>
Chun Kum Chun, head delegate of the Democratic People's
Republic Korea (DPRK), told a press conference this morning that
the North wanted the fertilizer aid first to help relieve its
natural disasters, before coming to the reunion issue.
</P>
<P>
The South demanded too much, he said, adding "The South's
method is `we give you a bowl of rice, then you should give us 10
kilograms of beef."
</P>
<P>
"Under such circumstances," he said, he was pessimistic for the
prospects of restoring governmental level contacts between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the fertilizer aid should be treated as an economic
and humanitarian issue without any pre-conditions. "We're not
begging for it. We could manage without fertilizer aid from
the South because of our self-reliance policy," he said.
</P>
<P>
The South said it would provide fertilizer to the North only
after it agreed to opening a new round of working level talks on
April 25 at the village of Panmunjom to discuss the reunion issue.
</P>
<P>
"We'll never trade our sovereignty for material gains," Chun
said, adding that the North made major concessions when it agreed
to come to the current talks.
</P>
<P>
Jeong Se Hyun, head of the Republic of Korea (ROK) delegation,
said that the door is not closed to further talks and hoped the
North changes its stance to come back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
He suggested a government envoy meeting be held before June.
</P>
<P>
Jeong reiterated that the 200,000-tons fertilizer aid would not
be shipped to the North unless it agreed to a date to open a
reunion meeting place at the border.
</P>
<P>
"We could not break down the barrier of mistrust," he said.
</P>
<P>
The North informed the South midnight, Friday, that it was
unnecessary to hold any more sessions, as the South would stand
firm by its position, thus leading the talks to an end.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the DPRK delegation will remain in Beijing while
the ROK delegation will leave for home tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said although the talks yielded no progress,
it had laid down some bases for the improvement of the
South-North relations and its symbolic meaning is far-reaching
after a four-year break between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The talks started April 11, and five delegates from each side
attended. The DPRK proposed Beijing as the venue for the talks and
the ROK agreed.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Foreign Ministry declined to comment on the outcome
of the week-long Beijing talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
