<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Firm Proposes to Build Container Terminals in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- A US-Bangladesh joint venture firm
has proposed to set up and operate container terminals in
Chittagong and Dhaka, and run container barge service between
these two points, The Financial Express daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In its integrated proposal submitted to the Bangladeshi
Ministry of Shipping, the joint venture firm, Stevedoring Services
of America (SSA), stated that it would need to invest about 438
million U.S. dollars to implement the project.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Shipping has sent a summary on the proposal to
the Council Committee on Economic Affairs seeking its approval
after examining the SSA's proposal, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Shipping has proposed for acquisition of land
by the government in Chittagong for handing over to the SSA for
setting up container terminals and container yards.
</P>
<P>
It also proposed for sale or lease-out of land already acquired
by a local firm for building an inland port in Dhaka to the SSA.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi side stated in its summary that with its vast
experience in implementing this type of project in many countries,
the SSA would be able to establish container terminals and yards
in Dhaka and Chittagong in two to three years.
</P>
<P>
The operation of container terminals and berths and running of
container barge service between Dhaka and Chittagong would go a
long way to resolving the congestion and operation problems at
Chittagong port, the newspaper noted.
</P>
<P>
According to SSA's proposal, it would set up 1070-meter long
container berth and a container yard and other backyard facilities
on 98 hectares of land in Chittagong, 224 kilometers southeast of
Dhaka, and a 450-meter long container berth and a container yard
on the south bank of Buriganga river in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the SSA would procure all types of equipment as
required to operate container terminal and berth, and would run
ten container barges between the two cities.
</P>
<P>
In the proposal, the SSA also stated that it would be able to
handle about 300,000 containers with the facilities established by
them.
</P>
<P>
At present, yearly growth rate in container movement through
Chittagong port is 15 percent. The port handled 290,000 containers
in the 1996-97 fiscal year. By the year 2002-2003, the port will
have to handle 671,000 containers if the growth rate in container
handling remained static. 
</P>
</TEXT>
