<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 percent Teachers in California Uncredentialed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Almost 10 percent of teachers
in California have no proper credentials, San Francisco Examiner
reported.
</P>
<P>
Of the 218,000 teachers in California, about 20,000 did not
have a teaching certificate last year, according to a preliminary
report by the state Commission on Teacher Credentialing.
</P>
<P>
Because of the drive to cut class size in kindergarten through
third grade, schools in California hire teachers with emergency
permits or waivers.
</P>
<P>
Teachers with emergency permits generally have some classroom
experience and are working toward their credentials. Those hired
on waivers may have no classroom experience but must earn a
teaching credential within five years of being hired.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, primary-level emergency credentials have increased 115
percent and secondary-level credentials 22 percent. Of the 18,600
teachers hired since 1996, the overwhelming majority were beginning
teachers or teachers on waivers or emergency permits.
</P>
<P>
To earn a teaching credential, candidates must have a bachelor's
degree, complete a one-year program of teaching methodology, spend a
semester as a student and pass a test of basic skills.
</P>
<P>
The challenge of finding qualified teachers is increasingly acute
in California, the most populous state in the country, because a
record number of teachers will soon retire, and the student population
is expected to surge by one million to 6.4 million by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, more than 50,000 people have entered teaching on
emergency or waiver permits in recent years, And 28 percent of
teachers lack either an academic minor or major in their assigned
subjects, according to the National Center for Education Statistics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
