<HEADLINE> Portugal Sees China as Strategic Partner: Guterres </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China is an important strategic
partner in Portugal's foreign relations, especially in its future
relations with Asian countries, says Portuguese Prime Minister
Antonio Guterres.
</P>
<P>
Guterres was speaking to Chinese correspondents here on the eve
of his visit to China scheduled to begin Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said his visit was aimed at enhancing confidence and
understanding between the two countries as well as promoting
Portuguese investment in China.
</P>
<P>
He said he wanted to deliver a political message to the
Portuguese business circle through his visit, encouraging them to
give priority to China in internationalizing their enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Guterres gave a positive evaluation of the Portuguese-Chinese
relations, saying the two countries enjoyed a good political
relationship.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to meet Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji during his
stay in Beijing, which he described as a further expression of the
friendly cooperation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The Portuguese prime minister said he saw great significance
and potential in developing mutually beneficial cooperation with
China in political, economic, and science and technology fields.
</P>
<P>
Portugal, in the capacity of a member country of the European
Union, was willing to play a positive part in promoting Euro-Asia
relations, especially Sino-European Union relations.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Macao, Guterres said he recognized the special
significance and the inevitable course of history in China's
resumption of exercising its sovereignty over Macao on December
31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that his government would assume an active, earnest
manner and full trust in the future Special Administrative Region
of Macao in the bid to ensure smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
He was fully confident the transition of Macao would help
strengthen the existing friendly relations between Portugal and
China. 
</P>
