<HEADLINE> S'pore, Malaysia PMs Open 2nd Link Between 2 Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong and Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad jointly
opened on Saturday the Malaysia-Singapore Second Link, which was
described by Goh as "an important milestone in Singapore-Malaysia
relations."
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers signed a commemorative plaque and
jointly cut a ribbon to signify the official opening of the Second
Link, which bridges Tanjung Kupang in Johor, Malaysia, and Tuas in
western Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Goh said that the Malaysia-Singapore Second Crossing is not
just another great engineering feat. It is the symbol of a new
phase in Malaysia-Singapore relationship.
</P>
<P>
The Second Crossing will open up new areas for collaboration
between the private sectors of the two countries, he said, adding,
"This is a bridge to the future; it is for future needs."
</P>
<P>
The 1.9-km Second Crossing, or otherwise called Second Link,
was actually opened to traffic on January 2 this year, after
almost four years of construction work by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The project is a fast way for Singaporeans to reach the
North-South Highway in Malaysia and will help ease the jam on the
Causeway, the first link between Woodlands, Singapore, and Johor
Baru, Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
