<HEADLINE> Albanian Parliament Calls for NATO Troops in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Albania's parliament called for
the deployment of NATO troops in Serbia's Kosovo province on
Friday, the Albanian news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A motion adopted by deputies said NATO deployment would prevent
the current unrest in Kosovo from spreading to other parts of the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The motion also asked U.S. President Bill Clinton to set up a
"red line" in Kosovo to protect ethnic Albanians there from being
attacked.
</P>
<P>
It called for the United Nations, all the European political
organizations, and the U.S. Congress to reconsider the Kosovo
issue and take effective measures.
</P>
<P>
The parliament backed Kosovo's Albanians in their quest for
political autonomy and urged the government to formulate a
detailed plan, according to the motion.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo, a Serbian province with an ethnic Albanian majority,
has sunk into chaos since ethnic Albanians calling for
independence from Serbia clashed with local Serb police. 
