<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of Thailand Wants More Foreign Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Governor of the Bank of Thailand
Chaiyawat Wilbulswasdi has called for more assistance from
industrialized countries to help reverse the economic turmoil in
the region.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the international community has a meaningful,
though differing, role to play in the resolution of the crisis
which is no longer domestic, nor regional in nature," Chaiyawat
said in remarks published by Saturday's Bangkok Post.
</P>
<P>
He said industrialized countries could influence not only the
pace, but also the direction, of how the crisis in one country
would be resolved.
</P>
<P>
Chaiyawat made the remarks as financial officials from the
Group of Seven nations and some Asian countries were meeting in
Washington to address the economic woes in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The concerted efforts within the region, Chaiyawat said, were
"a necessary but not sufficient, condition for the recovery."
</P>
<P>
"A more active participation by the countries in a strong
position is very much needed and thus called for," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand, in its efforts to seek more international
aid, was committed to improving transparency in policy and the
disclosure of economic and financial data.
</P>
<P>
The financial sector reform, he said, was moving quickly, with
the closure of unviable finance companies and the recapitalization
and tougher standards imposed on operating banks and financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand had created favorable conditions for more
foreign investment. He cited the appreciation of the baht against
the dollar and inflation below projections.
</P>
<P>
He said a current account surplus for 1998 is forecast at more
than four percent of gross domestic product, compared with a
deficit of two percent last year and 7.9 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Chaiyawat agreed that although the situation had stabilized in
recent months, the crisis was far from over.
</P>
<P>
"Affected countries like Thailand are taking necessary, though
painful, steps to resolve the crisis and revitalize our
economies," he said.
</P>
<P>
"However, the major risks now lie more in the external
environment -- the risk of higher trade protectionism, and
declining investment and trade financing, and most importantly,
the occurrence of adverse systemic developments in the advanced
economies," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
