<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Banana Sector Seeks Better Image </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Costa Rican banana industry
is planning a series of activities to counter a growing concern
among Europeans regarding the health and welfare of banana workers.
</P>
<P>
Some European countries have accused Costa Rica of not showing
the proper concern for the working conditions or basic rights of
banana workers.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the industry's institutional council and the
labor union for the plantation workers met Tuesday to analyze the
labor problems and seek solutions to improve Costa Rica's image in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Luis Umana, Banana Institutional Council director, said the
meeting also aims to increase sales of Costa Rican bananas to
international markets and erase the bad image of the sector.
</P>
<P>
There is a lot of misinformation and ignorance in Europe about
the conditions of Costa Rican banana workers, Umana said.
</P>
<P>
He, however, added that quality of the fruit, social and labor
stability, and the environmental conditions must be improved.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica is the second largest exporter of bananas in the
world after Ecuador. The country exported 101 million boxes of
bananas in 1997, earning 545 million U.S. dollars. 
