<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alcohol Lobby Gives U.S. Congress Millions of Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A new study shows that over
the past decade the alcoholic beverages lobby has made 26 million
dollars in political contributions to Congressional candidates, as
well as the Democratic and Republican parties.
</P>
<P>
The study, issued Friday by public interest group Common Cause,
shows Speaker Newt Gingrich was the top recipient in the House of
Representatives, taking in 163,243 dollars. Senator Mitch
McConnell, a Republican, led in the Senate, receiving 112,627
dollars from the alcohol lobby in the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Other leading recipients included Representative Vic Fazio, a
Democrat, at 115,952 dollars; Senator Kay Baily Hutchison, a
Republican, at 99,750 dollars, and Senate Democratic leader Tom
Daschle, at 97,399 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The study, which covers January 1987 to December 1997,
indicates that the alcohol lobby gave more than 16.7 million
dollars in political action contributions to House and Senate
candidates, and donated to political parties more than 9.4 million
dollars in soft-money contributions -- the unregulated donations
supposed to be used for party-building activities such as
get-out-the-vote drives.
</P>
<P>
The alcohol industry recently succeeded in keeping Congress
from adopting a nationwide blood-alcohol content level of 0.08 for
drunken driving, which Common Cause attributes to the money the
lobby has given to candidates and the political parties.
</P>
<P>
Common Cause President Ann McBride said: "The alcohol lobby has
become drunk with power by using big money to undermine public
safety. By caving in to the alcohol lobby, Congress is guilty of a
DUI, -- 'deciding under the influence,' -- the influence of more
than 26 million dollars in campaign contributions."
</P>
<P>
Among the leading contributors were the National Beer
Wholesalers Association, the National Restaurant Association,
Joseph E. Seagram &AMP; Son, and Anheuser-Busch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
