<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Forest Fires Cause 625 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia has lost over 5
trillion rupiah (625 million U.S. dollars) in timber revenues due
to fires which have ravaged more than 283,000 hectares of forest
in East Kalimantan province, a local official said.
</P>
<P>
Head of the provincial office of the Environmental Impact
Management Agency Awang Faroek Ishak said Friday in Samarinda,
capital of East Kalimantan province, that fires had destroyed at
least 105,900 hectares belonging to logging concessionaires,
75,000 hectares on timber estate areas and 71,000 hectares in
Kutai National Park, reports reaching here Saturday said.
</P>
<P>
He said the disaster had also damaged forestry by-products such
as wood resin and rattan. It has also destroyed some of the area's
natural biodiversity, a loss which is "unaccountable".
</P>
<P>
Intensive efforts to put out the fires, which started in
January this year, have so far proven futile.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to extinguish the blazes -- blamed largely on big
companies and farmers using slash-and-burn methods to clear land
for planting -- have generally been unsuccessful in the
drought-stricken province where little rain has been recorded
since last July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
