<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Vows to Return GSP Privileges to 4 Thai Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States has pledged to
return the tax privileges under its generalized system of
preferences (GSP) to four Thai products in return for the Thai
government's measures to protect intellectual property against
violations, according to the Bangkok Post Saturday.
</P>
<P>
USTR assistant Don Phillips, who is visiting Thailand, has
promised the tax privileges return to four items - silver
ornaments, non-silver ornaments, furniture and artificial flowers,
Banphot Hongthong, chief of the Intellectual Property Department
of the Thai government was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Don Phillips' presence here followed up on Washington's
commitment to the GSP-related issues made to Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai during his last month's official visit to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Banphot said the USTR is satisfied with mechanisms invented by
the Thai government to deter intellectual property fraud. They
include the establishment of the intellectual property court which
has finished deliberating over 500 cases since its inception four
months ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
