<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Adopts New Rules to Curb Software Piracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government has
introduced new regulations to curb software piracy at the source,
national newspaper the Straits Times reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules, makers of optical disks, including compact
disks (CDs) and video CDs used for computer software and movies,
are now compelled to obtain licenses to import the equipment
needed to manufacture master copies and duplicate the disks.
</P>
<P>
And the new regulations allow only manufacturers approved by
the government Economic Development Board (EDB) to import
mastering and replication equipment for CDs, CD-read only memory
(CD-ROM), video CDs, digital video disks (DVD) and DVD-ROMs.
</P>
<P>
One of the conditions for approval is an undertaking not to
violate intellectual property rights. Those who violate this
condition will have their licenses to manufacture revoked, the
report said, citing a statement issued by the EDB, the Ministry of
Trade and Industry, and the Trade Development Board (TDB).
</P>
<P>
It said that approved manufacturers also need TDB approval to
transfer the equipment to another company, re-export it after use,
or to dispose of it as scrap.
</P>
<P>
Nine local optical disk manufacturers signed a code of conduct
on Friday in which they undertook to help in the fight against
piracy by ensuring copyright is protected, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
