<HEADLINE> "El Nino" Brings More Fish to Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Fishing along the western
coast of Mexico improved markedly during the 1997 winter season as
the "El Nino" phenomenon improved the size of many catches for
fishermen there.
</P>
<P>
Ensenada, a city on the country's Pacific coast, reported a
20-percent increase in the size of catches in 1997, an official
with the Natural Resources and Fishing Ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said Mexico's fishery income rose to 70 million U.S. dollars
between 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, the "El Nino" also brought storms and swells to the
region that prevented fishermen from making more fishing trips.
</P>
<P>
The "El Nino," which means "The Baby" in Spanish, is a warm
tide that often occurs in the eastern Pacific Ocean during the
Christmas season that leads to widespread climate changes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
