<HEADLINE> Illiteracy Action Takes Off in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese government has vowed to
enable 3.5 million young and middle-aged illiterates to learn to
read and write this year.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper "China Daily" today quoted
an official from the Ministry of Education as saying that this is
a part of a bid to reduce the country's illiteracy rate for these
age groups from the current six percent to below two percent by
2000.
</P>
<P>
Educational departments across the country were urged to step
up efforts and increase funds to ensure that the goal is achieved.
</P>
<P>
To reach this goal, at least 3.5 million young and middle-aged
illiterates a year for the next three years must learn to read and
write, said Huang Yao, director of the ministry's department for
Adult Education, at a recently concluded ministerial conference.
</P>
<P>
Huang said the action applies especially to those living in
remote and poor areas, since it should enable them to master the
skills of shaking off poverty.
</P>
<P>
The education ministry and the Ministry of Finance will also
give awards to people making contributions to the nationwide
anti-illiteracy drive, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Preserve of Ancient Heritage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Pingyao heard the happy news at
the end of 1997, that Unesco had added this ancient town to its
World Cultural Heritage List, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
Located in North China's Shanxi Province, Pingyao is believed
to be one of the few places in China where people can still see
what a Chinese county seat looked like centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
Pingyao was originally established as a military stronghold
more than 2,700 years ago. Situated on the eastern bank of the
Fenhe River, a branch of the Yellow River, and at the northern
foot of Taiyue Mountain, Pingyao had a very advantageous military
location at that time.
</P>
<P>
Pingyao has remained a county seat since 221 BC when China was
first united as a kingdom. The current town of Pingyao was built
in 1370 during the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644), and its layout and
the architecture of its buildings are typical of that time.
Covering an area of more than two square kilometers, the
historical city is so well preserved it is said that it would be
possible for residents who lived there 600 years ago to know their
way around today.
</P>
<P>
In Pingyao, once headquarters for big commercial firms from the
17th century to the 1930s, visitors can explore the one-glorious
banking business of Shanxi by strolling around the remains of
Piaohao, the province's earliest banks. China's first money
exchange shop, Rishengchang, was established there in the early
19th century as a result of local economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the local government is co-operating in the
construction of a new town nearby where factories and residential
zones will be moved.
</P>
<P>
This move will help preserve Pingyao's precious cultural
heritage from the kind of damage that would certainly come with
undirected change, the paper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Cabinet Adopts Three-Year Economic Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Italian cabinet adopted a
three-year economic plan on Friday and pledged to reduce the
budget deficit and the national debt.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which covered the period from 1999 to 2001, also
pledged to increase investment for development and create more
jobs.
</P>
<P>
"This is an economic plan for sustainable economic
development," said Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
He said that after these measures go into effect, the gross
domestic product (GDP) will increase by 2.7 percent and the
national debt will be reduced to 107.1 percent of the GDP. The
budget deficit will also be reduced to one percent of the GDP,
while the inflation rate will remain at 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the revenue of the government will increase by
4.00 trillion lire (2.24 billion U.S. dollars), while government
expenditure will be reduced by 9.50 trillion lire (5.32 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government will appropriate 26.6 trillion lire (14.9
billion dollars) for development investment so that 600,000 more
jobs can be created. 
</P>
</TEXT>
