<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuchma Says Ukraine's Foreign Policy to Remain Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
told a foreign ministry meeting that the dismissing of Hennady
Udovenko does not mean a change in the country's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma named career diplomat Borys Tarasyuk as Ukraine's new
foreign minister on Friday, replacing Udovenko, who quit earlier
this month to take up a seat in parliament, said the
Interfax-Ukraine news agency.
</P>
<P>
Tarasyuk, 49, was ambassador to the Benelux countries (Belgium,
Holland and Luxemburg) and NATO until receiving the new job.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko, a member of the People's Movement party, won a
parliamentary seat in the March 29 election and under Ukrainian
law had to leave his cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma told diplomats that "Ukraine's foreign policy must not
be pro-Western or pro-Eastern."
</P>
<P>
Valery Pustovoitenko, prime minister of Ukraine, said a more
united action should be apparent within the government as a result
of the personnel change.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko said the major task of the foreign ministry this
year is to implement the Ukrainian-Russian economic cooperation
pact signed on February 27. The prime minister also said the
foreign ministry must ensure the annual meeting in May of the
European Bank of Reconstruction and Development.
</P>
<P>
Tarasyuk also told reporters that Ukraine's foreign policies
must always focus on the national interest.
</P>
<P>
He said the pacts signed with the Kremlin in the past years are
the foundations for the strategic partnership between the two
countries. This partnership should contain more concrete actions,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
