<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban, Northern Alliance Agree to Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Taliban militia and the
anti-Taliban Northern Alliance have agreed to hold face-to-face
talks for the first time in over a year, U.S. President's special
envoy Bill Richardson said here Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here at the American Center after
a day-long visit to Afghanistan, Richardson said the Taliban and
the Northern Alliance agreed to hold the proposed talks scheduled
for April 27 in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
"We hope this meeting under U.N. and OIC (Organization of
Islamic Conference) auspices will be the first step on a path to a
negotiated peace in Afghanistan," Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed not to launch new military offensives
until they meet in face-to-face talks in Islamabad later this
month, he said.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no further military offensives, and the two
sides would discuss the proposal of holding of an Ulema (scholar)
Commission meeting, for permanent ceasefire and establishing a
broad-based government in Afghanistan", Richardson added.
</P>
<P>
Richardson arrived here Wednesday evening on a three-day visit.
He met with the Pakistani leaders including Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif and Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan and held extensive
discussions on matters concerning the Afghan and Kashmir issues.
</P>
<P>
The special envoy visited Afghanistan Friday where he met
separately with second most senior Taliban leader Mullah Rabbani,
leader of the Northern Alliance Burhanuddin Rabbani, Uzbek ethnic
warlord General Rashid Dostam and Hezbi-Wadat Chairman Kharim
Khalili.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters soon after his day-long visit to
Afghanistan, Richardson said the agreement reached Friday between
the two Afghan rival factions would not have been possible without
the active support of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said that on humanitarian assistance, the two Afghan
factions agreed to enable relief workers to work in a safe and
secure environment, to work in accordance with internationally
accepted standards.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban and the Northern Alliance also agreed not to permit
terrorism from the Afghan soil and to combat drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
On the Northern Alliance side, they agreed "to support strongly
a negotiated settlement to lead to a broad-based government, to
set up their efforts to protect humanitarian personnel and
property and to accept a U.N. special rapporteur to investigate
human rights abuses," according to Richardson.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, on the Taliban side, they agreed to meet the U.N.
team on April 20, to allow Afghan female doctors to provide care
for women and girls, as well as allow the U.N. to hire Afghan
women to deliver humanitarian assistance to women and girls,
Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
"As a good-faith gesture, the Taliban said they will release a
few prisoners in the next couple of days," he added.
</P>
<P>
The special envoy said that "this was not a solitary effort on
the part of the U.S. It was part of the six plus two process led
by the U.N. Envoy to Afghanistan, Lakdhir Brahimi."
</P>
<P>
The Six plus two includes Afghanistan's neighboring states,
plus the U.S. and Russia.
</P>
<P>
On the agreement reached between the Taliban and the Northern
Alliance, Richardson said, "what will really matter is not what
they said today, but what they'll do in the days ahead."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
