<HEADLINE> Italians Strict with Officials: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A recent poll shows many Italians
are iron-hearted towards scandal-tainted officials but rather
lenient towards petty offenses of law.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Census, which polled some 2,000 people in its
latest research on criminality and justice in the country, said 95
percent of those polled wanted officials to resign if they were
involved in scandals.
</P>
<P>
Close to 40 percent said officials should resign the minute
they come under investigation.
</P>
<P>
As many as 54 percent of those polled agreed that the Clean
Hand anti-corruption operation had been a valid instrument for
cleaning up the country's political and public administration
systems.
</P>
<P>
The study, however, suggested widespread indulgence of petty
crimes among Italians, who believe petty offenses do not
constitute a threat to society.
</P>
<P>
Among those polled, 40 percent said breaking the law was
admissible in certain cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
