<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Li People Experience Profound Economic Growth (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a result, a large number of key construction projects have
been completed over the years, such as an expressway between
Haikou and the port city of Sanya, the Sanya Phoenix Airport and
the expansion of the Sanya Port, whose handling capacity of 5.4
million tons per year is about half of the combined handling
capacity of all ports in Hainan.
</P>
<P>
To date all telephones in Hainan's ethnic minority areas are
program-controlled while all long-distance transmission is
digitalized.
</P>
<P>
"The updating of our statistics often cannot catch up with the
rate at which great changes take place in the minority areas," a
provincial official said.
</P>
<P>
Over the last 10 years, Hainan's ethnic minority areas have
utilized one billion U.S. dollars of overseas investment, which
has helped to fund more than 900 construction projects.
</P>
<P>
For all the visible changes, the ethnic minority people
consider their development of market ideas as more significant
than anything else.
</P>
<P>
"We used to know nothing about how to plant vegetables and felt
ashamed of doing business," said Lan Chunhua, head of a village of
Li people.
</P>
<P>
But today, Lan is leading his villagers to plant and peddle
vegetables as well as to do business in processing and
transportation.
</P>
<P>
"Market economy ideas and the idea of becoming rich through
diligence have taken deep roots in people's heart," said Li
Mingtian, a Miao people and also vice chairman of CPPCC Hainan
Provincial Committee.
</P>
<P>
"These are ideas that we never dreamed of," he said.
</P>
<P>
Because of the construction drive in the last 10 years,
Hainan's poverty-ridden population has dropped from 870,000 to
250,000 people. More than 500,000 ethnic minority people have
moved out of thatched huts and into bright and spacious
tile-roofed and brick-walled houses.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that the gross domestic product of Hainan
areas inhabited by ethnic minorities soared fivefold rise between
1987 and 1997, during which the per capita income of the
province's rural residents jumped from 430 yuan to 1,318 yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
