<HEADLINE> Chile, Mexico Sign Free Trade Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Chile and Mexico signed a free
trade agreement on the eve of the Second Summit of the Americas
scheduled here for April 18-19.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was signed by the presidents of Chile, Eduardo Frei,
and Mexico, Ernesto Zedillo, who is here to attend the summit.
</P>
<P>
The treaty replaces and amplifies the Economic Complementation
Accord signed here also by the two countries on September 27,
1991, which went into force on January 1, 1992.
</P>
<P>
The new treaty accelerates full access to each other's markets
and the process of incorporating products in the list of
exceptions, which has been reduced, to the list of full exemptions
for trade between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agree in the treaty that export subsidies for
agricultural and livestock goods will be eliminated by January 1,
2003, while subsidies for non-agricultural products will be
governed by commitments made to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
Mexican Secretary of Foreign Relations Rosario Green and
Chilean Finance Minister Eduardo Aninat also signed, on behalf of
their respective governments, an agreement to prevent double
taxation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
President Zedillo said during the signing ceremony that the
agreements mean the two countries are fulfilling their obligations
to help integrate the continent.
</P>
<P>
President Frei said the treaty reflects the political will of
Latin American countries to make the integration real, a long
awaited dream of the region.
</P>
<P>
Both presidents think the agreements will promote commercial
exchanges and investments between the two countries based on
previous agreements and their achievements.
</P>
<P>
There has been a significant increase in commercial exchanges
between them because of the Economic Complementation Accord. The
total value of bilateral trade has increased from 158 million
U.S. dollars in 1990, to 1.452 billion dollars in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
