<HEADLINE> China's Li People Experience Profound Economic Growth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- In a trip to a village in south
China's island province of Hainan five years ago, Chinese
President Jiang Zemin heaped praise on Li Dehui and his family for
their success in developing a courtyard economy.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said he was encouraged by news that Li and his family
made an annual income of more than 70,000 yuan, a huge sum by
Chinese standards even today.
</P>
<P>
Li and his family deserved the appreciation of Jiang, who has
also been General Secretary of the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China, for they were  the first and only
well-off family at that time in Wenmen Village, Tianya Town of
Sanya, China's southernmost city.
</P>
<P>
Five years later, Li's family is no longer so special as more
and more of the Li ethnic group have begun to catch up.
</P>
<P>
"Today there are many people with incomes at the same level of
mine," Li told Xinhua in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
Like many other ethnic minority people, the 1.2 million Li
people on Hainan Island, which was part of Guangdong Province
until it was made a province and China's largest special economic
zone 10 years ago, have experienced rapid economic growth during
the past decade.
</P>
<P>
"The last 10 years marked the most rapid economic growth in the
history of Hainan areas inhabited by ethnic minority groups," said
Wang Jiaxian, also of the native Li group.
</P>
<P>
"I have seen with my own eyes the great changes that have taken
place in my hometown," said Wang, who is vice chairman of the
Hainan Provincial Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC), the country's top advisory body.
</P>
<P>
The changes are, most of all, reflected by significant
improvement in the infrastructure facilities in areas of ethnic
minority groups.
</P>
<P>
The central and provincial governments have over the last 10
years invested more than 22.6 billion yuan to improve the
infrastructure in areas populated by ethnic minorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
