<HEADLINE> Ancient Murals Record Events in Life of Sakyamuni </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Some 12 ancient murals recording
the life of Sakyamuni were recently discovered in the Mtho-ldin
Temple in the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Experts have identified the ancient artifacts as the fourth
kind of such paintings related to the life of the founder of
Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
The temple, the largest of its kind in western Tibet, is
located in Ngari Prefecture which was home to a flourishing
kingdom some 300 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The three-year excavation project yielded more than 20 wall
paintings, statues of Buddha and incomplete Buddhist sutras.
</P>
<P>
The excavations also yielded a cache of building materials,
including door jambs, thresholds and flights of stairs. Experts
note that the articles will provided a basis for future
reconstruction projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
