<HEADLINE> Italy, U.S. Call for Direct Dialogue in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Italy and the United States called
on those parties involved in the ethnic conflict in the Serbian
province of Kosovo to end the violence and open dialogue
immediately.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after a meeting on Friday, Italian
Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini and American Assistant Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott demanded that Serbian police "respect human
rights," and ethnic Albanians in Kosovo "explicitly renounce the
pursuit of political ends through force."
</P>
<P>
The two parties should "launch direct dialogue without delay"
and begin negotiations on what sort of autonomous status Kosovo
should have, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Talbott, who flew to Rome Friday from Bonn, is currently on a
tour of European capitals to seek a consensus on a plan of action
to resolve the ethnic tension in Kosovo which have reportedly
claimed at least dozens of lives since February.
</P>
<P>
The statement went on to stress that a solution must be found
to respect the territorial integrity of the Yugoslav Republic,
human rights and the international rules on ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
So far ethnic Albanians in Kosovo have refused Serbia's
invitation to join talks on autonomy; they are insisting on
secession. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
