<HEADLINE> Inter-Korean Talks Ends without Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) - The first inter-Korean high-level
contact broke down here today after a week-long fruitless talks,
and no date was decided for a possible resumption.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) delegation
has declared an end to the talks.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the DPRK said that it was unnecessary for the two
five-member delegations to meet again as scheduled this morning.
</P>
<P>
"It is meaningless to have any further talks. We'll not attend
any further meetings today," the sources said, adding that the
Republic of Korea (ROK) stands firm by their conditions attached
to the fertilizer aid issue.
</P>
<P>
At 9:00 A.M. today, the ROK delegation will hold a press
conference, followed by one to be given by the DPRK side.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday, Chun Kum Chul, chief delegate of the DPRK, said that
the South should not link the fertilizer aid with the reunion of
separated families, hinting the talks may end Saturday otherwise.
</P>
<P>
"If the South ships the fertilizer to the North, talks on the
reunion issue can begin immediately when the Red Cross talks
resume," Chun said.
</P>
<P>
Jeong Se Hyun, leader of the ROK delegation, reiterated his
position that the North should agree to a timetable to help
reunite separated families in return for fertilizer aid from the
South.
</P>
<P>
The 200,000 tons of fertilizer that the ROK offers can be
delivered this year, but the fertilizer aid and reunion issues
must be discussed simultaneously at the current talks, he stated.
</P>
</TEXT>
