<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major U.S., Asian Airlines Confident in Far East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The recent decision by United
Airlines to suspend daily nonstop service between San Francisco
and Seoul has not affected other major U.S. and Asian airlines.
</P>
<P>
In fact, those airlines and San Francisco International Airport
continue to express confidence in an economic recovery in the Far
East. Some airlines are even adding flights in the region.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Chicago-based United said it would suspend its San
Francisco-Seoul fight on May 5 "in light of the current economic
crisis." It would also suspend flights between Osaka, Japan, and
Seoul beginning July 8. "Korea has been particularly hard hit
during the crisis, and we have been unable to achieve sustained
profitability on those routes," United said.
</P>
<P>
The United announcement has not seemed to dim the ongoing
expansion of San Francisco International Airport. The expansion,
costing 2.4 billion U.S. dollars, includes a new international
terminal, based on projections that San Francisco will serve a
huge, developing Asian market in years to come -- particularly in
China.
</P>
<P>
Those projections remain unchanged, airport officials said,
despite a 12.8 percent decline in passengers to and from Asia when
comparing 188,300 passengers this February with 237,500 a year
ago. The airport said that passenger decline would be not be a
long-term trend.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of Singapore Airlines in Los Angeles has also
expressed similar conviction that the market will return in the
next two years. The company anticipates no schedule changes in
light of the economic downturn, although it has put passengers on
smaller airplanes on some routes when bookings decline.
</P>
<P>
In much of Asia, airlines are actually increasing their routes.
</P>
<P>
United is increasing service between Chicago and Japan and Hong
Kong, China.
</P>
<P>
TWA has been given authority for its first route, St. Louis to
Tokyo, beginning in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Japan Airlines will add a flight between San Francisco and
Tokyo in July.
</P>
<P>
Korean Airlines also said that no changes are planned in
service to and from Seoul, San Francisco and other U.S. and
Canadian cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980418.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF, World Bank Close Spring Meetings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) and the World Bank closed their spring meetings after
the bank's Development Committee finished a session Friday by
urging strengthening of the financial system.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day meetings, finance leaders focused on the
Asian financial crisis and ways to prevent and resolve such
crises.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting of the World Bank Development
Committee, Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim, the
meeting's chairman, said that if the international financial
system is not strengthened, "the problems may even exacerbate."
</P>
<P>
He also noted that there should be more cooperation between
the bank and the fund in crisis prevention and management.
</P>
<P>
"The committee encouraged strongly that the bank and the fund
continue to work together to get a collaboration, because the
issues and demands tend to be more complex," he said.
</P>
<P>
The committee urged the bank and the fund "to review and
reinforce their partnership based on their respective mandate,"
said a communique after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"This partnership has become even more important in light of
the growing significance of structural factors in assisting
member governments, and the increased demands on both
institutions," it added.
</P>
<P>
Members of the committee agreed that the implications of the
Asian financial crisis severely damaged the development
achievements in the region, particularly its "especially effective
anti-poverty performance," said the communique.
</P>
<P>
"Ministers urged the bank... to strengthen its ability to
address rapidly situations of this kind and to help governments
avoid such crises in the future," it added.
</P>
<P>
The committee urged the bank to assist countries in
strengthening key institutions and structural policies, and to
augment its skills and capacities in the financial sector,
corporate restructuring and governance and other areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
