<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges U.S.-Chilean Partnership for 21st </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
renewed here Friday his call for a strong partnership between the
United States and Chile as the world is entering the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
While addressing the joint sitting of the National Congress at
Valparaiso, the U.S. leader spoke highly of the democratic
development on this hemisphere and the bilateral relations between
his country and Chile.
</P>
<P>
"Chile and the United States must be full partners in the 21st
century," he stressed. "We must also be full partners with
like-minded democracies throughout our region."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also called for pursuance of "a second generation of
reforms" that are beyond free elections and free markets. He urged
the leaders to ensure that the "political system, the legal
system, the economic system are not rigged to favor those who
already have much, but instead give everyone a stake in shaping
the future."
</P>
<P>
According to the U.S. leader, "a second generation of reform"
requires a strong and independent legislature to represent all the
people, but also requires fighting against corruption, protecting
the environment and attacking threats to it, as well as raising
the level of education and people's life.
</P>
<P>
Chile is a shining star in America's constellation -- stable
and resilient with budget surpluses, a high savings rate, a high
growth rate, low unemployment, and low inflation, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president concluded his two-day state visit to Chile
Friday before joining other 33 leaders of the Americas in the
Second Summit scheduled for April 18.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the leaders of the two countries agreed to
broaden the scope of trade ties by establishing a U.S.-Chile Joint
Commission on Trade and Investment. Since 1993, the bilateral
trade between Chile and the U.S. has grown at an average of 13
percent a year, which reached 6.7 billion U.S. dollars in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
