<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Futures Tumble in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Crude oil futures tumbled
Friday, giving back gains made Thursday on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, after the U.N. secretary-general said he was pleased
with the inspection program searching out Iraqi chemical and
biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
A bumbling happened in crude futures after a U.N. spokesman
quoted Secretary-General Kofi Annan as saying he was "pleased with
the unlimited access" U.N. inspectors have had in searching Iraqi
palaces where weapons labs are suspected to be hidden.
</P>
<P>
Further lifting crude futures was news that Iraq had demanded
the Security Council lift economic sanctions when it meets this
month to review the status of Baghdad's weapons program.
</P>
<P>
Crude for May delivery fell 44 cents, or 2.8 percent, to 15.46
U.S. dollars a barrel. May heating oil and unleaded gasoline also
fell.
</P>
<P>
Cotton futures fell sharply on the New York Cotton Exchange.
</P>
<P>
July cotton fell 1.28 cents, or 1.9 percent, to 63.78 cents a
pound. 
</P>
