<HEADLINE> Syrian FM: Prospects of Ties With Qatar Bright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The prospects of the
Syrian-Qatari ties were promising as Damascus and Doha have
overcome their past differences, Syria's Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Sharaa said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at Damascus International Airport where
he welcomed his Qatari counterpart Sheikh Hamad Bin Jassim Bin Jabir
al-Thani, al-Sharaa said that "the prospects of bilateral ties are
bright and promising."
</P>
<P>
Al-Thani arrived here on Friday evening for an official visit
to Syria after touring Algeria and Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that al-Thani's visit to Syria will serve as an
opportunity for exchanging views and clearing the positions of
both countries to serve bilateral and Arab interests," al-Sharaa
said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that there are no disputes between Syria and Qatar,
adding "we believe that the reasons that led to a kind of
laxity in bilateral relations were removed."
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Qatari relations underwent a period of coldness
after Qatar's decision to allow Israel to open a trade office in
its capital Doha.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, Al-Thani said Qatar hopes Israel would
unconditionally pull out its troops from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"Qatar is seriously considering shutting down the Israeli trade
office in Doha due to the continuation of the deadlock in the
peace process," Al-Thani added.
</P>
<P>
Asked about reports on the probability of holding an Arab
summit, the Qatari official said if there is a reason for holding
a mini or expanded summit, "we would welcome such a summit as
Qatar is keen on maintaining a consensus and clear position (among
the Arabs) on the current Israeli intransigence."
</P>
<P>
The two ministers later held talks on the latest developments
in the region and ways of promoting bilateral ties, according to
the spokesman of the Syrian Foreign Ministry. 
</P>
