<HEADLINE> Wall Street Sets New Highs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street bounced
back Friday with several market indexes rising just high enough to
set new records.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average erased an early 23-point drop
and jumped 90.93 points to 9,167.50. It has erased Thursday's
85-point slide and edging past Wednesday's closing record of
9,162.27.
</P>
<P>
The Dow's gain in this week has been extended to 274.64 points.
Thus far this year, the Dow has gained about 1,250 points, or 16
percent, more than doubling the expectation of market analysts
for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 662.11 million
shares, down from Thursday's heft tally of 695.39 million.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 14.54 to 1,122.71,
squeaking past the April 3's record close at 1,122.70.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 8.35 to 1,866.59, topping
Thursday's record finish at 1,863.26.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 7.20 to 584.11, beating that
measure's previous best close of 583.17 on April 6.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.60 to
487.01, pushing past the April 2 record of 486.43.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange composite index rose 5.02 to
744.37, but still sits about 3 points from a new high.
</P>
<P>
American Express rose sharply to lead the Dow's advance after
Business Week said the company might merge with American
International Group to compete with Citigroup, a new financial
giant from a merger of Citicorp with the Travelers Group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
