<HEADLINE> Security Council to Deploy U.N. Military Liaison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The security Council of
the United Nations Friday decided to deploy 10 U.N. military
liaison officers in Sierra leone.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the council reviewed U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan's latest report on the situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
In its resolution unanimously adopted, the council said the
mandate of the U.N. military liaison officers is up to 90 days,
and its task is to work under the authority of the special envoy
of the secretary-general, to coordinate closely with the
government of Sierra Leone and the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) and its Military Observer Group (ECOMOG),
to report on the military situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the resolution, the U.N. officers are also
expected to assist in the finalization of planning by the ECOMOG
for future tasks, such as the identification of the former
combatant elements to be disarmed and the design of a disarmament
plan, as well as to perform other related security tasks.
</P>
<P>
The council urged all states and international organizations to
provide urgent humanitarian assistance to Sierra Leone and to
assist and participate in the longer term tasks of reconstruction
and economic and social recovery and development in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
