<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair: EU to Contribute More to Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Visiting British Prime Minister
Tony Blair said here Friday that the European Union (EU) can make
further contribution to the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak after their talks, Blair said the EU is making a
major contribution to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that Europe uses that role as constructively
as possible for the progress of all," said Blair.
</P>
<P>
If the peace process does not move forward, it will be very
dangerous, he said, adding that the aim of his visit "is to try
and move the process forward." Britain is now holding the rotating
presidency of the EU.
</P>
<P>
"We don't expect we will come cross U.S. efforts but rather
make a complimentary role to what the American's has been doing,"
Blair said.
</P>
<P>
Blair arrived here Friday afternoon on a two-day visit to Egypt
as part of his multi-leg maiden tour of the Middle East aimed at
giving a shot to the stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The British prime minister is making the tour after a week of
the signing of the peace agreement in Northern Ireland. He said
some lessons should be drawn from the signing of the agreement and
expressed the hope that the lessons could be used to make progress
in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
A peace agreement was signed last Friday by the British and
Irish governments and eight political parties in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Mubarak said the EU's role is very important,
adding that it should not be independent to the U.S. role, but it
should rather complete the U.S. role. If it is independent, it
will not be helpful, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reached an understanding that the Mideast peace
process should move forward, otherwise negative actions will
follow.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said his talks with Blair covered bilateral relations
and other issues.
</P>
<P>
As for bilateral ties, Blair said bilateral relations are very
strong, and they will get stronger.
</P>
<P>
Blair, on his debut trip to the region since taking office last
year, will explore prospects for stronger ties with Egypt during
his meetings with Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal El-Ganzouri and
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa Saturday.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, he is also scheduled to meet with members of the
British-Egyptian businessmen Association to examine the
possibility of increasing joint investments.
</P>
<P>
Blair's tour comes at a time when Europe is urged to play a more
active role in the stalemated Mideast peace process, especially
since the U.S.-dominated mediation efforts have so far failed to
unlock the peace logjam. U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross will
begin a new round of shuttle diplomacy in the region in the coming
days.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, who toured the region
last month, was snubbed in Israel allegedly for breaching an
understanding on the arrangements of his visit to the Har Homa in
East Jerusalem. Israel's Jewish settlement construction work at
the site is behind the long freeze in Palestinian-Israeli talks.
</P>
<P>
Britain has made it clear that the status of Jerusalem, the
thorniest issue in the Palestinian-Israeli track, should be
decided at the final stage of their negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Israel has repeatedly rejected European involvement in the
peace process, favoring an absolute mediating role for the
United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
