<HEADLINE> Saudi Industrial Investments Total 55 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The industrial long-standing
policy of Saudi Arabia has brought about tangible results in the
past two decades as total industrial investments increased from
2.7 billion U.S. dollars in 1975 to 55 billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait News Agency quoted a statistical abstract published
Friday as saying that the estimated overall number of running
plants in Saudi Arabia at the end of 1997 were 2674, with 73 of
them within the framework of joint Saudi-foreign capital
investments.
</P>
<P>
On top of the 1997 industrial list are the number of
petrochemical and plastic plants totaling 521, with total
investments of 36.6 billion dollars. They are followed by 490
construction, ceramics and glass plants with 6.19 billion dollars
of investments.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Basic Industries Company, the pioneer in the field of
petrochemical industries, has an annual petrochemical production
of up to 23 million tonnes, with a future plan to upgrade
production to 28 million tonnes by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
The number of metal and equipment manufacturing plants which
rank the third are 727 with 4.27 billion dollars of investments.
</P>
<P>
There are 415 foodstuffs and beverages plants with 3.3 billion
dollars of investments. Various other plants have investments
of 4.64 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The tangible growth of Saudi industries over the past 22 years
underlines the kingdom's policy of diversifying income sources
apart from the mainstay of oil as the only source of income in the
world top oil producer and exporter.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia's oil reserves accounts for 10 percent of the
world proven reserves and currently produces more than 8 million
barrel of oil per day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
