<HEADLINE> US Trade Deficit Increases 4.2 Percent in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The American trade deficit
climbed by 4.2 percent to 12.1 billion U.S. dollars in February,
the worst showing since the Administration began tracking these
figures on a monthly basis in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The new report, released Friday by the Commerce Department,
showed that the imbalance with Japan increased by 21 percent to
5.3 billion dollars from 4.4 billion dollars the previous month.
Meanwhile, the U.S. trade gap with many other Asian countries
struggling with financial crisis actually improved.
</P>
<P>
The American deficit with China narrowed by 17.5 percent to 3.5
billion dollars in February, a figure believed to be still bigger
than the Chinese account. The shortfall with Korea plunged 31.1
percent and that with Indonesia shrank by 8.2 percent, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
It is feared that a widening trade deficit would stir more
criticism of the U.S. Administration's free trade policy in
Congress and result in more pressure on the Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton and other government officials have
stepped up pressure on Japan to do its part to help the Asian
countries embroiled in the currency crisis and to provide a bigger
market for U.S. exports.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. deficit with Japan for February showed that U.S.
exports to Japan hit their lowest level in three years.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Undersecretary of Commerce for International Affairs
Robert Shapiro told reporters Friday:" We expect to see exports
rise from -- certainly from the countries that have been
struggling with currency problems. I don't have evidence that Japan
is trying to -- has changed policy in any way to increase exports
to the United States."
</P>
<P>
The official said that the Asian crisis will produce a drag on
U.S. economic growth. However, he added, "Declining exports to
Asia are offset to a very significant degree by the domestic
strength of the American economy."
</P>
<P>
"The exports -- U.S. exports to China have been growing for
some time. They (Chinese) have opened various sectors to American
investment. It continues to grow. It's showed very strong growth
thus far this year. Until we see other evidence, I see it as a
continuation of a pattern that's been in place for some time,"
Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
However, some economists still believed that the deficit in
coming months with Asia will swell as the full impact of the
economic turbulences in the region are felt.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
