<HEADLINE> Trade Shows Go Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Omni Group, a U.S. company based
in Chapel Hill, North Carolina, announces spring show opening on
April 24, 1998, which will be on line 24 hours a day and seven
days a week with a world wide exposure.
</P>
<P>
The show site http://www.worldwideexpo.com/ is still under busy
construction, the company said.
</P>
<P>
On April 24, exhibitors will begin the World Wide Expo's spring
show: A three month show featuring inventors, entrepreneurs and
service providers. The company said show exhibition spaces for the
spring show are filling rapidly. Potential exhibitors who wish to
take part in this new marketing wave need to move fast "due to
limited exhibition spaces."
</P>
<P>
After the WORLD WIDE EXPO's exploded onto Internet last
January, a total of 32,758 people visited it during the first week
on line.
</P>
<P>
Like their exhibition hall counterpart, the pavilions at the
World Wide Expo offer the opportunity to sample of both
traditional and cutting edge goods and services.
</P>
<P>
For a fee that is less than a daily ad in a local newspaper,
exhibitors receive global exposure in a variety of media,
including radio, print, and television. Unlike the typical Expo
hall, all of this is available from the comfort of your home or
office.
</P>
<P>
Virtual reality real estate tours and vacation spot demos with
360 panoramic "walk through" use the most sophisticated technology
available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The company said that what people miss from the World Wide Expo
are crowds, noise, long walks, standing in line and most time and
space limitations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
